# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: optics-physics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] In classical physics, diffraction is described by the Huygens–Fresnel principle that treats each point in a propagating wavefront as a collection of individual spherical wavelets.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] The patterns are due to the summation over different points on the wavefront (or, equivalently, each wavelet) that travel by paths of different lengths to the registering surface.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] If there are multiple closely spaced openings, a complex pattern of varying intensity can result.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] Other types of apertures or obstacles lead to different patterns, some of which are described later on this page.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] It plays a role in many areas, ranging from security devices on credit cards to methods of determining the atomic structure of materials at the nanoscale.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] Italian scientist Francesco Maria Grimaldi coined the word diffraction and was the first to record accurate observations of the phenomenon in 1660.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] After that various equivalent formulations were derived; mathematically, diffraction is explained by solving the wave equation for electromagnetic waves, or Schroedinger's equation for matter waves, in some cases with relativistic corrections.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] The effects of diffraction of light were first carefully observed and characterized by Francesco Maria Grimaldi, who also coined the term *diffraction*, from the Latin *diffringere*, 'to break into pieces', referring to light breaking up into different directions.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] The results of Grimaldi's observations were published posthumously in 1665.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] Isaac Newton studied these effects and attributed them to *inflexion* of light rays.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] James Gregory (1638–1675) observed the diffraction patterns caused by a bird feather, which was effectively the first diffraction grating to be discovered.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] Thomas Young developed the first wave treatment of diffraction in 1800.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] In his model Young proposed that the fringes observed behind an illuminated sharp edge arose from interference between the direct transmitted plane wave and a cylindrical wave that appears to emitted from the edge.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] Augustin-Jean Fresnel revisited the problem and devised an alternative wave theory based on Huygens' principle.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] In this model, point sources of light are distributed up to the diffraction edge but not in the barrier.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] These point sources are driven by the incoming plane wave and they interfere beyond the barrier.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] Fresnel developed a mathematical treatment from his approach and Young's model was initially considered incorrect.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] Later work showed that Young's more physical approach is equivalent to Fresnel's mathematical one.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] In 1818, supporters of the corpuscular theory of light proposed that the Paris Academy prize question address diffraction, expecting to see the wave theory defeated.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] When Fresnel's presentation on his new theory based on wave propagation looked like it might take the prize, Siméon Denis Poisson challenged the Fresnel theory by showing that it predicted light in the shadow behind a circular obstruction.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] Dominique-François-Jean Arago proceeded to demonstrate experimentally that such light is visible, confirming Fresnel's diffraction model.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] In 1859 Hermann von Helmholtz and later in 1882 Gustav Kirchhoff developed integral equations for diffraction based on the concepts proposed by Fresnel as well as approximations needed to apply them.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] In general, all these approaches require formulating the problem in terms of virtual sources.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] Cases like those with an absorbing barrier require methods developed in the 1940s based on transverse amplitude diffusion.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] Diffraction is a general phenomenon of waves, occurring whenever a wave encounters some form of obstruction.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] The obstruction may be solidly blocking the wave, or transparent and shifting the phase of the wave without any change in energy (elastic scattering).
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] The waves beyond the obstacle interfere leading to a diffraction pattern.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] The diffraction pattern cannot be predicted by the straight line trajectories of geometrical optics.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] For a simple example, a strong light source blocked by a solid object does not show a crisp dark shadow when examined carefully.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] The appropriate model for diffraction depends upon the character of the waves and the obstructions.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] The simplest model uses the Huygens–Fresnel principle.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] The Huygens part visualizes propagation of a wave by considering every point on a wavefront as a source for a secondary spherical wave, these being called **Huygens wavelets**.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] The Fresnel part is the superposition (linear sum) of these secondary waves and their consequent interference.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] In the absence of obstacles, the Huygens's principle alone predicts wavefront propagation.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] When some of the secondary waves are blocked by an obstacle, the remainder will create both wavefront propagation in the unblocked direction and waves behind the obstacle which form the diffraction pattern.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] When waves are added together, their sum is determined by their relative phases as well as the amplitudes of the individual waves, so that the summed amplitude can have any value between zero and the sum of the individual amplitudes.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] Hence, diffraction patterns usually have a series of maxima and minima.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] In quantum mechanics, diffraction is also described in terms of a wave, but the wavefunction represents a probability amplitude whose modulus squared is the probability of detection.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] The light and dark regions in diffraction patterns are then areas where the quanta are more or less likely to be detected.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] Most configurations cannot be solved analytically, but can yield numerical solutions through finite element and boundary element methods.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] In many cases it is assumed that there is only one scattering event, what is called kinematical diffraction, with an Ewald's sphere construction used to represent that there is no change in energy during the diffraction process.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] For matter waves a similar but slightly different approach is used based upon a relativistically corrected form of the Schrödinger equation, as first detailed by Hans Bethe.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] The Fraunhofer and Fresnel limits exist for these as well, although they correspond more to approximations for the matter wave Green's function (propagator) for the Schrödinger equation.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] Multiple scattering models are required in many types of electron diffraction; in some cases similar dynamical diffraction models are also used for X-rays.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] The simplest descriptions of diffraction are those in which the situation can be reduced to a two-dimensional problem.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] For water waves, this is already the case; water waves propagate only on the surface of the water.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] For light, we can often neglect one direction if the diffracting object extends in that direction over a distance far greater than the wavelength.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] In the case of light shining through small circular holes, we have to take into account the full three-dimensional nature of the problem.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] The effects of diffraction are often seen in everyday life.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] The most commonly encountered examples of diffraction are those that involve light; for example, the closely spaced tracks on a CD or DVD which act as a diffraction grating to form the familiar rainbow pattern seen when looking at a disc.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] This principle can be extended to engineer a grating with a structure such that it will produce any diffraction pattern desired; the hologram on a credit card is an example.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] Diffraction in the atmosphere by small particles can cause a corona—a bright disc and rings around a light source such as the Sun or the Moon.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] At the opposite point, one may observe a glory—bright rings around the shadow of the observer.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] In contrast to the corona, glory requires the particles to be transparent spheres (like fog droplets), since the backscattering of the light that forms the glory involves refraction and internal reflection within the droplet.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] Another frequently encountered example is diffraction spikes which are caused by a range of processes including a non‑circular aperture in a camera or by support struts in a telescope; in normal vision, diffraction through eyelashes may produce similar spikes.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] When deli meat appears iridescent, the effect is caused by diffraction from the meat fibres, as are the colors of a spider web; there are many other cases for light colors.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] While diffraction by light is the most common case encountered, diffraction can occur with any kind of wave, for instance ocean waves diffract around jetties and other obstacles.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] Sound waves can diffract around objects, which is why one can still hear someone calling even when hiding behind a tree.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] Other examples of diffraction are considered in more detail below.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] The diffraction patterns depend upon the nature of the obstacles the wave encounters, both their physical dimensions as well as how the change the phase and/or direction of the wave.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] The simplest types of obstacles are slits or apertures which block of part of the wave In the far-field / Fraunhofer region, Huygens' principle applied to the open region around such obstacles says that the far-field diffraction pattern is the spatial Fourier transform of the open region shape.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] This is a direct by-product of using the parallel-rays approximation, which is identical to doing a plane wave decomposition of the plane fields across the open region (see Fourier optics).
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] An illuminated slit that is wider than a wavelength produces interference effects in the space downstream of the slit.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] Assuming that the slit behaves as though it has a large number of point sources spaced evenly across the width of the slit, the interference effects can be calculated.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] If the incident light is a single wavelength and coherent, these sources all have the same phase.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] Light in the space downstream of the slit is made up of contributions from each of these point sources.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] If the relative phases of contributions from each point source vary due to differences in the path lengths, the resulting intensity will vary.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] Imagining the slit as the y axis with the z across the slit and x pointing downstream, intensity minima and maxima can be seen along z for large values of x.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] For points very close to x all the point sources are in phase.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] This is the undiffracted beam, forming a maximum.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] Moving away fom the x axis, the path length from the point sources in the center and those on the edges of the slit differ.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] When the path difference equals $\lambda /2$ , the central sources cancel the edge sources in destructive interference.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] This analysis applies only to the far field (Fraunhofer diffraction), that is, at a distance much larger than the width of the slit.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] The far-field diffraction pattern of a plane wave incident on a circular aperture is known as the Airy disk.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] The Airy disk has the following intensity distribution as a function of angle θ: $I(\theta )=I_{0}\left({\frac {2J_{1}(ka\sin \theta )}{ka\sin \theta }}\right)^{2},$ where a is the radius of the circular aperture, k is equal to $2\pi /\lambda$ and $J_{1}$ is a Bessel function.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] The smaller the aperture, the larger the spot size at a given distance, and the greater the divergence of the diffracted beams.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] For aperture diameters close to the wavelength of the light, the Airy disk begins to act like a point source with very large divergence of diffracted beams.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] An opaque body and a hole of the same size and shape as the opaque body are called *complementary* apertures: as diffraction apertures they sum to a completely open space.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] For example, a screen with a circular hole is complementary to a circular disk the same size as the hole.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] The optical effect E of these apertures add, $E_{\textrm {opaque}}+E_{\textrm {hole}}=E_{0}$ giving the optical effect, $E_{0}$ of no obstacle.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] This is Babinet's principle; it works well in the Fraunhofer diffraction limit.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] When $E_{0}\approx 0,$ $E_{\textrm {opaque}}=-E_{\textrm {hole}}$ so the intensity in the two patterns are the same everywhere.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] By imaging a point source through either aperture, the same pattern results every except right at the focal point.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] The **knife-edge effect** or **knife-edge diffraction** is a truncation of a portion of the incident radiation that strikes a sharp well-defined obstacle, such as a mountain range or the wall of a building.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] Knife-edge diffraction is an outgrowth of the "half-plane problem", originally solved by Arnold Sommerfeld using a plane wave spectrum formulation.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] A generalization of the half-plane problem is the "wedge problem", solvable as a boundary value problem in cylindrical coordinates.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] The solution in cylindrical coordinates was then extended to the optical regime by Joseph B.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] Keller, who introduced the notion of diffraction coefficients through his geometrical theory of diffraction (GTD).
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] In 1974, Prabhakar Pathak and Robert Kouyoumjian extended the (singular) Keller coefficients via the uniform theory of diffraction (UTD).
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] A diffraction grating is an optical component with a regular pattern.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] The light diffracted by a grating is found by summing the light diffracted from each of the elements, and is essentially a convolution of diffraction and interference patterns.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] The figure shows the light diffracted by 2-element and 5-element gratings where the grating spacings are the same; it can be seen that the maxima are in the same position, but the detailed structures of the intensities are different.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] A more mathematical approach involves treating the problem as a summation over spherical waves derived from the relevant wave equation; see for instance Born and Wolf for details.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] This solution assumes that the delta function source is located at the origin.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] with an electric field $E_{\mathrm {inc} }(x,y)$ incident on the aperture for the case of an electromagnetic wave.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] In the far-field / Fraunhofer region, this becomes the spatial Fourier transform of the aperture.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] In the far field, where r is essentially constant, then the equation: $\Psi =\int _{\mathrm {aperture} }{\frac {i}{r\lambda }}\Psi ^{\prime }e^{-ikr}\,d\mathrm {aperture}$ is equivalent to doing a Fourier transform on the gaps in the barrier.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] Similar forms can be derived for matter and other types of waves.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] For instance, with electron diffraction the aperture would be replaced by the electrostatic potential, while for x-ray diffraction it would be the electron charge density.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] In the cases discussed above it is implicitly assumed that the wave encounters some single barrier or obstruction and is then diffraction by it.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] In reality it may encounter a number of barriers along the direction that it is travelling.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] The wave diffraction by the first one it encounters can be diffraction by the next, and so forth.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] The case when only single diffraction occurs is called kinematical diffraction, the more general case is called dynamical diffraction.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] Dynamical diffraction is quite well developed for x-rays, and also for electrons.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] As discussed extensively in the existing literature and reviews the results with dynamical diffraction can be quite different from those when only single scattering is considered.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] It can also occur with light, one example being opals and photonic crystals.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] According to quantum theory every particle exhibits wave properties and can therefore diffract.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] Diffraction of electrons and neutrons is one of the powerful arguments in favor of quantum mechanics.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] The wavelength associated with a non-relativistic particle is the de Broglie wavelength $\lambda ={\frac {h}{p}}\,,$ where h is the Planck constant and p is the momentum of the particle (mass × velocity for slow-moving particles).
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] For example, a sodium atom traveling at about 300 m/s would have a de Broglie wavelength of about 50 picometres.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] Diffraction of matter waves has been observed for small particles, like electrons, neutrons, atoms, and even large molecules.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] The short wavelength of these matter waves makes them ideally suited to study the atomic structure of solids, molecules and proteins.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] Diffraction from a large three-dimensional periodic structure such as many thousands of atoms in a crystal is called Bragg diffraction.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] It is similar to what occurs when waves are scattered from a diffraction grating.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] Bragg diffraction is a consequence of interference between waves reflecting from many different crystal planes.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] The condition of constructive interference is given by *Bragg's law*: $m\lambda =2d\sin \theta ,$ where $\lambda$ is the wavelength, d is the distance between crystal planes, $\theta$ is the angle of the diffracted wave, and m is an integer known as the *order* of the diffracted beam.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] Bragg diffraction may be carried out using either electromagnetic radiation of very short wavelength like X-rays or matter waves like neutrons whose wavelength is on the order of (or much smaller than) the atomic spacing.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] The pattern produced gives information of the separations of crystallographic planes d , allowing one to deduce the crystal structure.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] For completeness, Bragg diffraction is a limit for a large number of atoms with X-rays or neutrons, and is rarely valid for electron diffraction or with solid particles in the size range of less than 50 nanometers.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] The description of diffraction relies on the interference of waves emanating from the same source taking different paths to the same point on a screen.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] In this description, the difference in phase between waves that took different paths is only dependent on the effective path length.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] This does not take into account the fact that waves that arrive at the screen at the same time were emitted by the source at different times.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] The initial phase with which the source emits waves can change over time in an unpredictable way.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] This means that waves emitted by the source at times that are too far apart can no longer form a constant interference pattern since the relation between their phases is no longer time independent.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] The length over which the phase in a beam of light is correlated is called the coherence length.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] In order for interference to occur, the path length difference must be smaller than the coherence length.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] This is sometimes referred to as spectral coherence, as it is related to the presence of different frequency components in the wave.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] In the case of light emitted by an atomic transition, the coherence length is related to the lifetime of the excited state from which the atom made its transition.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] If waves are emitted from an extended source, this can lead to incoherence in the transversal direction.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] When looking at a cross section of a beam of light, the length over which the phase is correlated is called the transverse coherence length.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] In the case of Young's double-slit experiment, this would mean that if the transverse coherence length is smaller than the spacing between the two slits, the resulting pattern on a screen would look like two single-slit diffraction patterns.
[src:optics-physics/diffraction] In the case of particles like electrons, neutrons, and atoms, the coherence length is related to the spatial extent of the wave function that describes the particle.
[src:optics-physics/lens] A **lens** is a transmissive optical device that focuses or disperses a light beam by means of refraction.
[src:optics-physics/lens] A simple lens consists of a single piece of transparent material, while a compound lens consists of several simple lenses (*elements*), usually arranged along a common axis.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Lenses are made from materials such as glass or plastic and are ground, polished, or molded to the required shape.
[src:optics-physics/lens] A lens can focus light to form an image, unlike a prism, which refracts light without focusing.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Devices that similarly focus or disperse waves and radiation other than visible light are also called "lenses", such as microwave lenses, electron lenses, acoustic lenses, or explosive lenses.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Lenses are used in various imaging devices such as telescopes, binoculars, and cameras.
[src:optics-physics/lens] They are also used as visual aids in glasses to correct defects of vision such as myopia and hypermetropia.
[src:optics-physics/lens] The word *lens* comes from *lēns*, the Latin name of the lentil (a seed of a lentil plant), because a double-convex lens is lentil-shaped.
[src:optics-physics/lens] The lentil also gives its name to a geometric figure.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Some scholars argue that the archeological evidence indicates that there was widespread use of lenses in antiquity, spanning several millennia.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Others argue that besides some use as burning glasses, most ancient 'lenses' must have been decorative rather than functional.
[src:optics-physics/lens] The Nimrud lens is a rock crystal artifact dated to the 7th century BCE which may or may not have been used as a magnifying glass, or a burning glass.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Others have suggested that certain Egyptian hieroglyphs depict "simple glass meniscal lenses".
[src:optics-physics/lens] The oldest certain reference to the use of a lens as a burning-glass is from Aristophanes's play *The Clouds* (424 BCE).
[src:optics-physics/lens] Pliny the Elder (1st century) confirms that burning-glasses were known in the Roman period.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Pliny arguably referred to the use of a corrective lens when he mentions that Nero was said to watch the gladiatorial games using an emerald (possibly concave to correct for nearsightedness, though the reference is confusing and this interpretation has been disputed.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Ptolemy (2nd century) wrote a book on *Optics*, which however survives only in the Latin translation of an incomplete and very poor Arabic translation.
[src:optics-physics/lens] The book was, however, received by medieval scholars in the Islamic world, and commented upon by Ibn Sahl (10th century), who was in turn improved upon by Alhazen (*Book of Optics*, 11th century).
[src:optics-physics/lens] The Arabic translation of Ptolemy's *Optics* became available in Latin translation in the 12th century (Eugenius of Palermo 1154).
[src:optics-physics/lens] Between the 11th and 13th century "reading stones" were used.
[src:optics-physics/lens] These were primitive plano-convex lenses initially made by cutting a glass sphere in half.
[src:optics-physics/lens] The medieval (11th or 12th century) rock crystal Visby lenses may or may not have been intended for use as burning glasses.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Spectacles were invented as an improvement of the "reading stones" of the high medieval period in Northern Italy in the second half of the 13th century.
[src:optics-physics/lens] This was the start of the optical industry of grinding and polishing lenses for spectacles, first in Venice and Florence in the late 13th century, and later in the spectacle-making centres in both the Netherlands and Germany.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Spectacle makers created improved types of lenses for the correction of vision based more on empirical knowledge gained from observing the effects of the lenses (probably without the knowledge of the rudimentary optical theory of the day).
[src:optics-physics/lens] The practical development and experimentation with lenses led to the invention of the compound optical microscope around 1595, and the refracting telescope in 1608, both of which appeared in the spectacle-making centres in the Netherlands.
[src:optics-physics/lens] With the invention of the telescope and microscope there was a great deal of experimentation with lens shapes in the 17th and early 18th centuries by those trying to correct chromatic errors seen in lenses.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Opticians tried to construct lenses of varying forms of curvature, wrongly assuming errors arose from defects in the spherical figure of their surfaces.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Optical theory on refraction and experimentation was showing no single-element lens could bring all colours to a focus.
[src:optics-physics/lens] This led to the invention of the compound achromatic lens by Chester Moore Hall in England in 1733, an invention also claimed by fellow Englishman John Dollond in a 1758 patent.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Developments in transatlantic commerce were the impetus for the construction of modern lighthouses in the 18th century, which utilize a combination of elevated sightlines, lighting sources, and lenses to provide navigational aid overseas.
[src:optics-physics/lens] With maximal distance of visibility needed in lighthouses, conventional convex lenses would need to be significantly sized which would negatively affect the development of lighthouses in terms of cost, design, and implementation.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Fresnel lens were developed that considered these constraints by featuring less material through their concentric annular sectioning.
[src:optics-physics/lens] They were first fully implemented into a lighthouse in 1823.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Most lenses are *spherical lenses*: their two surfaces are parts of the surfaces of spheres.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Each surface can be *convex* (bulging outwards from the lens), *concave* (depressed into the lens), or *planar* (flat).
[src:optics-physics/lens] The line joining the centres of the spheres making up the lens surfaces is called the *axis* of the lens.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Typically the lens axis passes through the physical centre of the lens, because of the way they are manufactured.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Lenses may be cut or ground after manufacturing to give them a different shape or size.
[src:optics-physics/lens] The lens axis may then not pass through the physical centre of the lens.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Toric or sphero-cylindrical lenses have surfaces with two different radii of curvature in two orthogonal planes.
[src:optics-physics/lens] They have a different focal power in different meridians.
[src:optics-physics/lens] An example is eyeglass lenses that are used to correct astigmatism in someone's eye.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Lenses are classified by the curvature of the two optical surfaces.
[src:optics-physics/lens] A lens is *biconvex* (or *double convex*, or just *convex*) if both surfaces are convex.
[src:optics-physics/lens] If both surfaces have the same radius of curvature, the lens is *equiconvex*.
[src:optics-physics/lens] A lens with two concave surfaces is *biconcave* (or just *concave*).
[src:optics-physics/lens] If one of the surfaces is flat, the lens is *plano-convex* or *plano-concave* depending on the curvature of the other surface.
[src:optics-physics/lens] A lens with one convex and one concave side is *convex-concave* or *meniscus*.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Convex-concave lenses are most commonly used in corrective lenses, since the shape minimizes some aberrations.
[src:optics-physics/lens] For a biconvex or plano-convex lens in a lower-index medium, a collimated beam of light passing through the lens converges to a spot (a *focus*) behind the lens.
[src:optics-physics/lens] In this case, the lens is called a *positive* or *converging* lens.
[src:optics-physics/lens] For a thin lens in air, the distance from the lens to the spot is the focal length of the lens, which is commonly represented by f in diagrams and equations.
[src:optics-physics/lens] An extended hemispherical lens is a special type of plano-convex lens, in which the lens's curved surface is a full hemisphere and the lens is much thicker than the radius of curvature.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Another extreme case of a thick convex lens is a ball lens, whose shape is completely round.
[src:optics-physics/lens] When used in novelty photography it is often called a "lensball".
[src:optics-physics/lens] A ball-shaped lens has the advantage of being omnidirectional, but for most optical glass types, its focal point lies close to the ball's surface.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Because of the ball's curvature extremes compared to the lens size, optical aberration is much worse than thin lenses, with the notable exception of chromatic aberration.
[src:optics-physics/lens] For a biconcave or plano-concave lens in a lower-index medium, a collimated beam of light passing through the lens is diverged (spread); the lens is thus called a *negative* or *diverging* lens.
[src:optics-physics/lens] The beam, after passing through the lens, appears to emanate from a particular point on the axis in front of the lens.
[src:optics-physics/lens] For a thin lens in air, the distance from this point to the lens is the focal length, though it is negative with respect to the focal length of a converging lens.
[src:optics-physics/lens] The behavior reverses when a lens is placed in a medium with higher refractive index than the material of the lens.
[src:optics-physics/lens] In this case a biconvex or plano-convex lens diverges light, and a biconcave or plano-concave one converges it.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Convex-concave (meniscus) lenses can be either positive or negative, depending on the relative curvatures of the two surfaces.
[src:optics-physics/lens] A *negative meniscus* lens has a steeper concave surface (with a shorter radius than the convex surface) and is thinner at the centre than at the periphery.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Conversely, a *positive meniscus* lens has a steeper convex surface (with a shorter radius than the concave surface) and is thicker at the centre than at the periphery.
[src:optics-physics/lens] An ideal thin lens with two surfaces of equal curvature (also equal in the sign) would have zero optical power (as its focal length becomes infinity as shown in the lensmaker's equation), meaning that it would neither converge nor diverge light.
[src:optics-physics/lens] All real lenses have a nonzero thickness, however, which makes a real lens with identical curved surfaces slightly positive.
[src:optics-physics/lens] To obtain exactly zero optical power, a meniscus lens must have slightly unequal curvatures to account for the effect of the lens' thickness.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Due to paraxial approximation where the line of *h* is close to the vertex of the spherical surface meeting the optical axis on the left, ${\textstyle u}$ and ${\textstyle v}$ are also considered distances with respect to the vertex.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Moving ${\textstyle v}$ toward the right infinity leads to the first or object focal length ${\textstyle f_{0}}$ for the spherical surface.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Similarly, ${\textstyle u}$ toward the left infinity leads to the second or image focal length $f_{i}$ .
[src:optics-physics/lens] Applying this equation on the two spherical surfaces of a lens and approximating the lens thickness to zero (so a thin lens) leads to the lensmaker's formula.
[src:optics-physics/lens] The focal length f is positive for converging lenses, and negative for diverging lenses.
[src:optics-physics/lens] The reciprocal of the focal length, ${\textstyle {\tfrac {1}{f}},}$ is the optical power of the lens.
[src:optics-physics/lens] If the focal length is in metres, this gives the optical power in dioptres (reciprocal metres).
[src:optics-physics/lens] Lenses have the same focal length when light travels from the back to the front as when light goes from the front to the back.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Other properties of the lens, such as the aberrations are not the same in both directions.
[src:optics-physics/lens] The signs of the lens' radii of curvature indicate whether the corresponding surfaces are convex or concave.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Consequently, for external lens surfaces as diagrammed above, *R*1 > 0 and *R*2 < 0 indicate *convex* surfaces (used to converge light in a positive lens), while *R*1 < 0 and *R*2 > 0 indicate *concave* surfaces.
[src:optics-physics/lens] The reciprocal of the radius of curvature is called the curvature.
[src:optics-physics/lens] A flat surface has zero curvature, and its radius of curvature is infinite.
[src:optics-physics/lens] This convention is used in this article.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Other conventions such as the Cartesian sign convention change the form of the equations.
[src:optics-physics/lens] If d is small compared to *R*1 and *R*2 then the thin lens approximation can be made.
[src:optics-physics/lens] The spherical thin lens equation in paraxial approximation is derived here with respect to the right figure.
[src:optics-physics/lens] where the subscript of 2 in ${\textstyle n_{2}}$ is dropped.
[src:optics-physics/lens] As mentioned above, a positive or converging lens in air focuses a collimated beam travelling along the lens axis to a spot (known as the focal point) at a distance f from the lens.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Conversely, a point source of light placed at the focal point is converted into a collimated beam by the lens.
[src:optics-physics/lens] These two cases are examples of image formation in lenses.
[src:optics-physics/lens] In the former case, an object at an infinite distance (as represented by a collimated beam of waves) is focused to an image at the focal point of the lens.
[src:optics-physics/lens] In the latter, an object at the focal length distance from the lens is imaged at infinity.
[src:optics-physics/lens] The plane perpendicular to the lens axis situated at a distance f from the lens is called the focal plane.
[src:optics-physics/lens] This is a simple ray tracing method easily used.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Two rays among the three are sufficient to locate the image point.
[src:optics-physics/lens] By moving the object along the optical axis, it is shown that the second ray determines the image size while other rays help to locate the image location.
[src:optics-physics/lens] where $x_{1}=S_{1}-f$ and $x_{2}=S_{2}-f\,.$ ${\textstyle x_{1}}$ is positive if it is left to the front focal point ${\textstyle F_{1}}$ , and ${\textstyle x_{2}}$ is positive if it is right to the rear focal point ${\textstyle F_{2}}$ .
[src:optics-physics/lens] Because ${\textstyle f^{2}}$ is positive, an object point and the corresponding imaging point made by a lens are always in opposite sides with respect to their respective focal points.
[src:optics-physics/lens] This Newtonian form of the lens equation can be derived by using a similarity between triangles *P*1*P*O1*F*1 and *L*3*L*2*F*1 and another similarity between triangles *L*1*L*2*F*2 and *P*2*P*02*F*2 in the right figure.
[src:optics-physics/lens] The similarities give the following equations and combining these results gives the Newtonian form of the lens equation.
[src:optics-physics/lens] This is because of triangle similarities like the thin lens case above; similarity between triangles *P*1*P*O1*F*1 and *L*3*H*1*F*1 and another similarity between triangles *L*1'*H*2*F*2 and *P*2*P*02*F*2 in the right figure.
[src:optics-physics/lens] If distances *S*1 or *S*2 pass through a medium other than air or vacuum, then a more complicated analysis is required.
[src:optics-physics/lens] If an object is placed at a distance *S*1 > *f* from a positive lens of focal length f, we will find an image at a distance *S*2 according to this formula.
[src:optics-physics/lens] If a screen is placed at a distance *S*2 on the opposite side of the lens, an image is formed on it.
[src:optics-physics/lens] This sort of image, which can be projected onto a screen or image sensor, is known as a *real image*.
[src:optics-physics/lens] This is the principle of the camera, and also of the human eye, in which the retina serves as the image sensor.
[src:optics-physics/lens] The focusing adjustment of a camera adjusts *S*2, as using an image distance different from that required by this formula produces a defocused (fuzzy) image for an object at a distance of *S*1 from the camera.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Put another way, modifying *S*2 causes objects at a different *S*1 to come into perfect focus.
[src:optics-physics/lens] In some cases, *S*2 is negative, indicating that the image is formed on the opposite side of the lens from where those rays are being considered.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Since the diverging light rays emanating from the lens never come into focus, and those rays are not physically present at the point where they *appear* to form an image, this is called a virtual image.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Unlike real images, a virtual image cannot be projected on a screen, but appears to an observer looking through the lens as if it were a real object at the location of that virtual image.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Likewise, it appears to a subsequent lens as if it were an object at that location, so that second lens could again focus that light into a real image, *S*1 then being measured from the virtual image location behind the first lens to the second lens.
[src:optics-physics/lens] This is exactly what the eye does when looking through a magnifying glass.
[src:optics-physics/lens] The magnifying glass creates a (magnified) virtual image behind the magnifying glass, but those rays are then re-imaged by the lens of the eye to create a *real image* on the retina.
[src:optics-physics/lens] lens produces a demagnified virtual image.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Using a positive lens of focal length f, a virtual image results when *S*1 < *f*, the lens thus being used as a magnifying glass (rather than if *S*1 ≫ *f* as for a camera).
[src:optics-physics/lens] Using a negative lens (*f* < 0) with a *real object* (*S*1 > 0) can only produce a virtual image (*S*2 < 0), according to the above formula.
[src:optics-physics/lens] It is also possible for the object distance *S*1 to be negative, in which case the lens sees a so-called *virtual object*.
[src:optics-physics/lens] This happens when the lens is inserted into a converging beam (being focused by a previous lens) *before* the location of its real image.
[src:optics-physics/lens] In that case even a negative lens can project a real image, as is done by a Barlow lens.
[src:optics-physics/lens] For a given lens with the focal length *f*, the minimum distance between an object and the real image is 4*f* (*S*1 = *S*2 = 2*f*).
[src:optics-physics/lens] This is derived by letting *L* = *S*1 + *S*2, expressing *S*2 in terms of *S*1 by the lens equation (or expressing *S*1 in terms of *S*2), and equating the derivative of *L* with respect to *S*1 (or *S*2) to zero.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Real image of a lamp is projected onto a screen (inverted).
[src:optics-physics/lens] Reflections of the lamp from both surfaces of the biconvex lens are visible.
[src:optics-physics/lens] may also be viewed when put on a screen.
[src:optics-physics/lens] where M is the magnification factor defined as the ratio of the size of an image compared to the size of the object.
[src:optics-physics/lens] The sign convention here dictates that if M is negative, as it is for real images, the image is upside-down with respect to the object.
[src:optics-physics/lens] For virtual images M is positive, so the image is upright.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Linear magnification M is not always the most useful measure of magnifying power.
[src:optics-physics/lens] For instance, when characterizing a visual telescope or binoculars that produce only a virtual image, one would be more concerned with the angular magnification—which expresses how much larger a distant object appears through the telescope compared to the naked eye.
[src:optics-physics/lens] In the case of a camera one would quote the plate scale, which compares the apparent (angular) size of a distant object to the size of the real image produced at the focus.
[src:optics-physics/lens] The plate scale is the reciprocal of the focal length of the camera lens; lenses are categorized as long-focus lenses or wide-angle lenses according to their focal lengths.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Using an inappropriate measurement of magnification can be formally correct but yield a meaningless number.
[src:optics-physics/lens] For instance, using a magnifying glass of 5 cm focal length, held 20 cm from the eye and 5 cm from the object, produces a virtual image at infinity of infinite linear size: *M* = ∞.
[src:optics-physics/lens] But the angular magnification is 5, meaning that the object appears 5 times larger to the eye than without the lens.
[src:optics-physics/lens] When taking a picture of the moon using a camera with a 50 mm lens, one is not concerned with the linear magnification *M* ≈ −50 mm / 380000 km = −1.3×10−10.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Rather, the plate scale of the camera is about 1°/mm, from which one can conclude that the 0.5 mm image on the film corresponds to an angular size of the moon seen from earth of about 0.5°.
[src:optics-physics/lens] In the extreme case where an object is an infinite distance away, *S*1 = ∞, *S*2 = *f* and *M* = −*f*/∞ = 0, indicating that the object would be imaged to a single point in the focal plane.
[src:optics-physics/lens] In fact, the diameter of the projected spot is not actually zero, since diffraction places a lower limit on the size of the point spread function.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Lenses do not form perfect images, and always introduce some degree of distortion or *aberration* that makes the image an imperfect replica of the object.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Careful design of the lens system for a particular application minimizes the aberration.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Several types of aberration affect image quality, including spherical aberration, coma, and chromatic aberration.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Different lens materials may also be used to minimise chromatic aberration, such as specialised coatings or lenses made from the crystal fluorite.
[src:optics-physics/lens] This naturally occurring substance has the highest known Abbe number, indicating that the material has low dispersion.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Other kinds of aberration include *field curvature*, *barrel*and *pincushion distortion*, and *astigmatism*.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Even if a lens is designed to minimize or eliminate the aberrations described above, the image quality is still limited by the diffraction of light passing through the lens' finite aperture.
[src:optics-physics/lens] A diffraction-limited lens is one in which aberrations have been reduced to the point where the image quality is primarily limited by diffraction under the design conditions.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Simple lenses are subject to the optical aberrations discussed above.
[src:optics-physics/lens] In many cases these aberrations can be compensated for to a great extent by using a combination of simple lenses with complementary aberrations.
[src:optics-physics/lens] A *compound lens* is a collection of simple lenses of different shapes and made of materials of different refractive indices, arranged one after the other with a common axis.
[src:optics-physics/lens] In a multiple-lens system, one can consider the image created by the first lens to be a virtual object for the next lens.
[src:optics-physics/lens] That lens creates an image of this virtual object, and in this way the imaging cascades through the lenses until the final image is produced by the last lens in the system.
[src:optics-physics/lens] As shown above, the Gaussian lens equation for a spherical lens is derived such that the 2nd surface of the lens images the image made by the 1st lens surface.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Following the same logic, in multi-lens imaging, the 3rd lens surface (the front surface of the 2nd lens) images the image made by the 2nd surface, and the 4th surface (the back surface of the 2nd lens) images the image made by the 3rd surface.
[src:optics-physics/lens] This imaging cascade by each lens surface justifies the imaging cascade by each lens.
[src:optics-physics/lens] For a two-lens system the object distances of each lens can be denoted as ${\textstyle s_{o1}}$ and ${\textstyle s_{o2}}$ , and the image distances as and ${\textstyle s_{i1}}$ and ${\textstyle s_{i2}}$ .
[src:optics-physics/lens] If the distance between the two lenses is d , then ${\textstyle s_{o2}=d-s_{i1}}$ .
[src:optics-physics/lens] FFD (Front Focal Distance) is defined as the distance between the front (left) focal point of an optical system and its nearest optical surface vertex.
[src:optics-physics/lens] If an object is located at the front focal point of the system, then its image made by the system is located infinitely far way to the right (i.e., light rays from the object is collimated after the system).
[src:optics-physics/lens] To do this, the image of the 1st lens is located at the focal point of the 2nd lens, i.e., $s_{i1}=d-f_{2}$ .
[src:optics-physics/lens] BFD (Back Focal Distance) is similarly defined as the distance between the back (right) focal point of an optical system and its nearest optical surface vertex.
[src:optics-physics/lens] If an object is located infinitely far away from the system (to the left), then its image made by the system is located at the back focal point.
[src:optics-physics/lens] In this case, the 1st lens images the object at its focal point.
[src:optics-physics/lens] A simplest case is where thin lenses are placed in contact ( $d=0$ ).
[src:optics-physics/lens] Since 1/*f* is the power of a lens with focal length f, it can be seen that the powers of thin lenses in contact are additive.
[src:optics-physics/lens] where ${\textstyle N}$ is the number of lenses.
[src:optics-physics/lens] As d tends to zero, the focal length of the system tends to the value of f given for thin lenses in contact.
[src:optics-physics/lens] It can be shown that the same formula works for thick lenses if d is taken as the distance between their principal planes.
[src:optics-physics/lens] If the separation distance between two lenses is equal to the sum of their focal lengths (*d* = *f*1 + *f*2), then the FFD and BFD are infinite.
[src:optics-physics/lens] This corresponds to a pair of lenses that transforms a parallel (collimated) beam into another collimated beam.
[src:optics-physics/lens] This type of system is called an *afocal system*, since it produces no net convergence or divergence of the beam.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Two lenses at this separation form the simplest type of optical telescope.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Although the system does not alter the divergence of a collimated beam, it does alter the (transverse) width of the beam.
[src:optics-physics/lens] which is the ratio of the output beam width to the input beam width.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Note the sign convention: a telescope with two convex lenses (*f*1 > 0, *f*2 > 0) produces a negative magnification, indicating an inverted image.
[src:optics-physics/lens] A convex plus a concave lens (*f*1 > 0 > *f*2) produces a positive magnification and the image is upright.
[src:optics-physics/lens] For further information on simple optical telescopes, see Refracting telescope § Refracting telescope designs.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Cylindrical lenses have curvature along only one axis.
[src:optics-physics/lens] They are used to focus light into a line, or to convert the elliptical light from a laser diode into a round beam.
[src:optics-physics/lens] They are also used in motion picture anamorphic lenses.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Aspheric lenses have at least one surface that is neither spherical nor cylindrical.
[src:optics-physics/lens] The more complicated shapes allow such lenses to form images with less aberration than standard simple lenses, but they are more difficult and expensive to produce.
[src:optics-physics/lens] These were formerly complex to make and often extremely expensive, but advances in technology have greatly reduced the manufacturing cost for such lenses.
[src:optics-physics/lens] A Fresnel lens has its optical surface broken up into narrow rings, allowing the lens to be much thinner and lighter than conventional lenses.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Durable Fresnel lenses can be molded from plastic and are inexpensive.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Lenticular lenses are arrays of microlenses that are used in lenticular printing to make images that have an illusion of depth or that change when viewed from different angles.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Bifocal lens has two or more, or a graduated, focal lengths ground into the lens.
[src:optics-physics/lens] A gradient index lens has flat optical surfaces, but has a radial or axial variation in index of refraction that causes light passing through the lens to be focused.
[src:optics-physics/lens] An axicon has a conical optical surface.
[src:optics-physics/lens] It images a point source into a line *along* the optic axis, or transforms a laser beam into a ring.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Diffractive optical elements can function as lenses.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Superlenses are made from negative index metamaterials and claim to produce images at spatial resolutions exceeding the diffraction limit.
[src:optics-physics/lens] The first superlenses were made in 2004 using such a metamaterial for microwaves.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Improved versions have been made by other researchers.
[src:optics-physics/lens] As of 2014 the superlens has not yet been demonstrated at visible or near-infrared wavelengths.
[src:optics-physics/lens] A prototype flat ultrathin lens with no curvature has been developed.
[src:optics-physics/lens] A single convex lens mounted in a frame with a handle or stand is a magnifying glass.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Lenses are used as prosthetics for the correction of refractive errors such as myopia, hypermetropia, presbyopia, and astigmatism.
[src:optics-physics/lens] (See corrective lens, contact lens, eyeglasses, intraocular lens.) Most lenses used for other purposes have strict axial symmetry; eyeglass lenses are only approximately symmetric.
[src:optics-physics/lens] They are usually shaped to fit in a roughly oval, not circular, frame; the optical centres are placed over the eyeballs; their curvature may not be axially symmetric to correct for astigmatism.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Sunglasses' lenses are designed to attenuate light; sunglass lenses that also correct visual impairments can be custom made.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Other uses are in imaging systems such as monoculars, binoculars, telescopes, microscopes, cameras and projectors.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Some of these instruments produce a virtual image when applied to the human eye; others produce a real image that can be captured on photographic film or an optical sensor, or can be viewed on a screen.
[src:optics-physics/lens] In these devices lenses are sometimes paired up with curved mirrors to make a catadioptric system where the lens's spherical aberration corrects the opposite aberration in the mirror (such as Schmidt and meniscus correctors).
[src:optics-physics/lens] Convex lenses produce an image of an object at infinity at their focus; if the sun is imaged, much of the visible and infrared light incident on the lens is concentrated into the small image.
[src:optics-physics/lens] A large lens creates enough intensity to burn a flammable object at the focal point.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Since ignition can be achieved even with a poorly made lens, lenses have been used as burning-glasses for at least 2400 years.
[src:optics-physics/lens] A modern application is the use of relatively large lenses to concentrate solar energy on relatively small photovoltaic cells, harvesting more energy without the need to use larger and more expensive cells.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Radio astronomy and radar systems often use dielectric lenses, commonly called a lens antenna to refract electromagnetic radiation into a collector antenna.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Lenses can become scratched and abraded.
[src:optics-physics/lens] Abrasion-resistant coatings are available to help control this.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Most optical phenomena can be accounted for by using the classical electromagnetic description of light, however, complete electromagnetic descriptions of light are often difficult to apply in practice.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Practical optics is usually done using simplified models.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] The most common of these, geometric optics, treats light as a collection of rays that travel in straight lines and bend when they pass through or reflect from surfaces.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Physical optics is a more comprehensive model of light, which includes wave effects such as diffraction and interference that cannot be accounted for in geometric optics.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Historically, the ray-based model of light was developed first, followed by the wave model of light.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Progress in electromagnetic theory in the 19th century led to the discovery that light waves were in fact electromagnetic radiation.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Some phenomena depend on light having both wave-like and particle-like properties.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Explanation of these effects requires quantum mechanics.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] When considering light's particle-like properties, the light is modelled as a collection of particles called "photons".
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Quantum optics deals with the application of quantum mechanics to optical systems.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Optical science is relevant to and studied in many related disciplines including astronomy, various engineering fields, photography, and medicine, especially in radiographic methods such as beam radiation therapy and CT scans, and in the physiological optical fields of ophthalmology and optometry.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Practical applications of optics are found in a variety of technologies and everyday objects, including mirrors, lenses, telescopes, microscopes, lasers, and fibre optics.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Optics began with the development of lenses by the ancient Egyptians and Mesopotamians.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] The earliest known lenses, made from polished crystal, often quartz, date from as early as 2000 BC from Crete (Archaeological Museum of Heraclion, Greece).
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Lenses from Rhodes date around 700 BC, as do Assyrian lenses such as the Nimrud lens.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] The ancient Romans and Greeks filled glass spheres with water to make lenses.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] These practical developments were followed by the development of theories of light and vision by ancient Greek and Indian philosophers, and the development of geometrical optics in the Greco-Roman world.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] The word *optics* comes from the ancient Greek word ὀπτική, *optikē* 'appearance, look'.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Greek philosophy on optics broke down into two opposing theories on how vision worked, the intromission theory and the emission theory.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] The intromission approach saw vision as coming from objects casting off copies of themselves (called eidola) that were captured by the eye.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] With many propagators including Democritus, Epicurus, Aristotle and their followers, this theory seems to have some contact with modern theories of what vision really is, but it remained only speculation lacking any experimental foundation.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Plato first articulated the emission theory, the idea that visual perception is accomplished by rays emitted by the eyes.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] He also commented on the parity reversal of mirrors in *Timaeus*.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Some hundred years later, Euclid (4th–3rd century BC) wrote a treatise entitled *Optics* where he linked vision to geometry, creating *geometrical optics*.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] He based his work on Plato's emission theory wherein he described the mathematical rules of perspective and described the effects of refraction qualitatively, although he questioned that a beam of light from the eye could instantaneously light up the stars every time someone blinked.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Euclid stated the principle of the shortest trajectory of light, and considered multiple reflections on flat and spherical mirrors.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Ptolemy, in his treatise *Optics*, held an extramission-intromission theory of vision: the rays (or flux) from the eye formed a cone, the vertex being within the eye, and the base defining the visual field.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] The rays were sensitive, and conveyed information back to the observer's intellect about the distance and orientation of surfaces.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] He summarized much of Euclid and went on to describe a way to measure the angle of refraction, though he failed to notice the empirical relationship between it and the angle of incidence.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Plutarch (1st–2nd century AD) described multiple reflections on spherical mirrors and discussed the creation of magnified and reduced images, both real and imaginary, including the case of chirality of the images.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] During the Middle Ages, Greek ideas about optics were resurrected and extended by writers in the Muslim world.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] One of the earliest of these was Al-Kindi (c.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] 801–873) who wrote on the merits of Aristotelian and Euclidean ideas of optics, favouring the emission theory since it could better quantify optical phenomena.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] In 984, the Persian mathematician Ibn Sahl wrote the treatise "On burning mirrors and lenses", correctly describing a law of refraction equivalent to Snell's law.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] He used this law to compute optimum shapes for lenses and curved mirrors.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] In the early 11th century, Alhazen (Ibn al-Haytham) wrote the *Book of Optics* (*Kitab al-manazir*) in which he explored reflection and refraction and proposed a new system for explaining vision and light based on observation and experiment.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Alhazen's work was largely ignored in the Arabic world but it was anonymously translated into Latin around 1200 A.D. and further summarised and expanded on by the Polish monk Witelo making it a standard text on optics in Europe for the next 400 years.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Grosseteste's most famous disciple, Roger Bacon, wrote works citing a wide range of recently translated optical and philosophical works, including those of Alhazen, Aristotle, Avicenna, Averroes, Euclid, al-Kindi, Ptolemy, Tideus, and Constantine the African.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Bacon was able to use parts of glass spheres as magnifying glasses to demonstrate that light reflects from objects rather than being released from them.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] The first wearable eyeglasses were invented in Italy around 1286.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] This was the start of the optical industry of grinding and polishing lenses for these "spectacles", first in Venice and Florence in the thirteenth century, and later in the spectacle making centres in both the Netherlands and Germany.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] This practical development, mastery, and experimentation with lenses led directly to the invention of the compound optical microscope around 1595, and the refracting telescope in 1608, both of which appeared in the spectacle making centres in the Netherlands.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] He was also able to correctly deduce the role of the retina as the actual organ that recorded images, finally being able to scientifically quantify the effects of different types of lenses that spectacle makers had been observing over the previous 300 years.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] After the invention of the telescope, Kepler set out the theoretical basis on how they worked and described an improved version, known as the *Keplerian telescope*, using two convex lenses to produce higher magnification.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Optical theory progressed in the mid-17th century with treatises written by philosopher René Descartes, which explained a variety of optical phenomena including reflection and refraction by assuming that light was emitted by objects which produced it.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] This differed substantively from the ancient Greek emission theory.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] In the late 1660s and early 1670s, Isaac Newton expanded Descartes's ideas into a corpuscle theory of light, famously determining that white light was a mix of colours that can be separated into its component parts with a prism.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] In 1690, Christiaan Huygens proposed a wave theory for light based on suggestions that had been made by Robert Hooke in 1664.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Hooke himself publicly criticised Newton's theories of light and the feud between the two lasted until Hooke's death.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] In 1704, Newton published *Opticks* and, at the time, partly because of his success in other areas of physics, he was generally considered to be the victor in the debate over the nature of light.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Newtonian optics was generally accepted until the early 19th century when Thomas Young and Augustin-Jean Fresnel conducted experiments on the interference of light that firmly established light's wave nature.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Young's famous double slit experiment showed that light followed the superposition principle, which is a wave-like property not predicted by Newton's corpuscle theory.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] This work led to a theory of diffraction for light and opened an entire area of study in physical optics.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Wave optics was successfully unified with electromagnetic theory by James Clerk Maxwell in the 1860s.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] The next development in optical theory came in 1899 when Max Planck correctly modelled blackbody radiation by assuming that the exchange of energy between light and matter only occurred in discrete amounts he called *quanta*.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] In 1905, Albert Einstein published the theory of the photoelectric effect that firmly established the quantization of light itself.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] In 1913, Niels Bohr showed that atoms could only emit discrete amounts of energy, thus explaining the discrete lines seen in emission and absorption spectra.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] The understanding of the interaction between light and matter that followed from these developments not only formed the basis of quantum optics but also was crucial for the development of quantum mechanics as a whole.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] The ultimate culmination, the theory of quantum electrodynamics, explains all optics and electromagnetic processes in general as the result of the exchange of real and virtual photons.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Quantum optics gained practical importance with the inventions of the maser in 1953 and of the laser in 1960.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Following the work of Paul Dirac in quantum field theory, George Sudarshan, Roy J.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Glauber, and Leonard Mandel applied quantum theory to the electromagnetic field in the 1950s and 1960s to gain a more detailed understanding of photodetection and the statistics of light.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Classical optics is divided into two main branches: geometrical (or ray) optics and physical (or wave) optics.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] In geometrical optics, light is considered to travel in straight lines, while in physical optics, light is considered as an electromagnetic wave.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Geometrical optics can be viewed as an approximation of physical optics that applies when the wavelength of the light used is much smaller than the size of the optical elements in the system being modelled.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] When a ray of light hits the boundary between two transparent materials, it is divided into a reflected and a refracted ray.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Geometric optics is often simplified by making the paraxial approximation, or "small angle approximation".
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] The mathematical behaviour then becomes linear, allowing optical components and systems to be described by simple matrices.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] This leads to the techniques of Gaussian optics and *paraxial ray tracing*, which are used to find basic properties of optical systems, such as approximate image and object positions and magnifications.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Reflections can be divided into two types: specular reflection and diffuse reflection.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Specular reflection describes the gloss of surfaces such as mirrors, which reflect light in a simple, predictable way.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] This allows for the production of reflected images that can be associated with an actual (real) or extrapolated (virtual) location in space.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Diffuse reflection describes non-glossy materials, such as paper or rock.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] The reflections from these surfaces can only be described statistically, with the exact distribution of the reflected light depending on the microscopic structure of the material.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Many diffuse reflectors are described or can be approximated by Lambert's cosine law, which describes surfaces that have equal luminance when viewed from any angle.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Glossy surfaces can give both specular and diffuse reflection.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] In specular reflection, the direction of the reflected ray is determined by the angle the incident ray makes with the surface normal, a line perpendicular to the surface at the point where the ray hits.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] The incident and reflected rays and the normal lie in a single plane, and the angle between the reflected ray and the surface normal is the same as that between the incident ray and the normal.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] For flat mirrors, the law of reflection implies that images of objects are upright and the same distance behind the mirror as the objects are in front of the mirror.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] The image size is the same as the object size.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] The law also implies that mirror images are parity inverted, which we perceive as a left-right inversion.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Images formed from reflection in two (or any even number of) mirrors are not parity inverted.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Corner reflectors produce reflected rays that travel back in the direction from which the incident rays came.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Mirrors with curved surfaces can be modelled by ray tracing and using the law of reflection at each point on the surface.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] For mirrors with parabolic surfaces, parallel rays incident on the mirror produce reflected rays that converge at a common focus.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Other curved surfaces may also focus light, but with aberrations due to the diverging shape causing the focus to be smeared out in space.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] In particular, spherical mirrors exhibit spherical aberration.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Curved mirrors can form images with a magnification greater than or less than one, and the magnification can be negative, indicating that the image is inverted.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] An upright image formed by reflection in a mirror is always virtual, while an inverted image is real and can be projected onto a screen.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Refraction occurs when light travels through an area of space that has a changing index of refraction; this principle allows for lenses and the focusing of light.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] The simplest case of refraction occurs when there is an interface between a uniform medium with index of refraction *n*1 and another medium with index of refraction *n*2.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] where *θ*1 and *θ*2 are the angles between the normal (to the interface) and the incident and refracted waves, respectively.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] The index of refraction of a medium is related to the speed, *v*, of light in that medium by $n=c/v,$ where *c* is the speed of light in vacuum.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Snell's Law can be used to predict the deflection of light rays as they pass through linear media as long as the indexes of refraction and the geometry of the media are known.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] For example, the propagation of light through a prism results in the light ray being deflected depending on the shape and orientation of the prism.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] In most materials, the index of refraction varies with the frequency of the light, known as dispersion.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Taking this into account, Snell's Law can be used to predict how a prism will disperse light into a spectrum.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] The discovery of this phenomenon when passing light through a prism is famously attributed to Isaac Newton.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Some media have an index of refraction which varies gradually with position and, therefore, light rays in the medium are curved.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] This effect is responsible for mirages seen on hot days: a change in index of refraction air with height causes light rays to bend, creating the appearance of specular reflections in the distance (as if on the surface of a pool of water).
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Optical materials with varying indexes of refraction are called gradient-index (GRIN) materials.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Such materials are used to make gradient-index optics.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] For light rays travelling from a material with a high index of refraction to a material with a low index of refraction, Snell's law predicts that there is no *θ*2 when *θ*1 is large.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] In this case, no transmission occurs; all the light is reflected.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] This phenomenon is called total internal reflection and allows for fibre optics technology.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] As light travels down an optical fibre, it undergoes total internal reflection allowing for essentially no light to be lost over the length of the cable.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] A device that produces converging or diverging light rays due to refraction is known as a *lens*.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Lenses are characterized by their focal length: a converging lens has positive focal length, while a diverging lens has negative focal length.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Smaller focal length indicates that the lens has a stronger converging or diverging effect.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] The focal length of a simple lens in air is given by the lensmaker's equation.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Ray tracing can be used to show how images are formed by a lens.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] where *S*1 is the distance from the object to the lens, *S*2 is the distance from the lens to the image, and f is the focal length of the lens.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] In the sign convention used here, the object and image distances are positive if the object and image are on opposite sides of the lens.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Incoming parallel rays are focused by a converging lens onto a spot one focal length from the lens, on the far side of the lens.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] This is called the rear focal point of the lens.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Rays from an object at a finite distance are focused further from the lens than the focal distance; the closer the object is to the lens, the further the image is from the lens.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] With diverging lenses, incoming parallel rays diverge after going through the lens, in such a way that they seem to have originated at a spot one focal length in front of the lens.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Rays from an object at a finite distance are associated with a virtual image that is closer to the lens than the focal point, and on the same side of the lens as the object.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] The closer the object is to the lens, the closer the virtual image is to the lens.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] As with mirrors, upright images produced by a single lens are virtual, while inverted images are real.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Lenses suffer from aberrations that distort images.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] *Monochromatic aberrations* occur because the geometry of the lens does not perfectly direct rays from each object point to a single point on the image, while chromatic aberration occurs because the index of refraction of the lens varies with the wavelength of the light.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] In physical optics, light is considered to propagate as waves.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] This model predicts phenomena such as interference and diffraction, which are not explained by geometric optics.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] The speed of light waves in air is approximately 3.0×108 m/s (exactly 299,792,458 m/s in vacuum).
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] The wavelength of visible light waves varies between 400 and 700 nm, but the term "light" is also often applied to infrared (0.7–300 μm) and ultraviolet radiation (10–400 nm).
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] The wave model can be used to make predictions about how an optical system will behave without requiring an explanation of what is "waving" in what medium.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Until the middle of the 19th century, most physicists believed in an "ethereal" medium in which the light disturbance propagated.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] The existence of electromagnetic waves was predicted in 1865 by Maxwell's equations.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] These waves propagate at the speed of light and have varying electric and magnetic fields which are orthogonal to one another, and also to the direction of propagation of the waves.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Light waves are now generally treated as electromagnetic waves except when quantum mechanical effects have to be considered.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Many simplified approximations are available for analysing and designing optical systems.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Most of these use a single scalar quantity to represent the electric field of the light wave, rather than using a vector model with orthogonal electric and magnetic vectors.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] The Huygens–Fresnel equation is one such model.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] This was derived empirically by Fresnel in 1815, based on Huygens' hypothesis that each point on a wavefront generates a secondary spherical wavefront, which Fresnel combined with the principle of superposition of waves.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] The Kirchhoff diffraction equation, which is derived using Maxwell's equations, puts the Huygens-Fresnel equation on a firmer physical foundation.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Examples of the application of Huygens–Fresnel principle can be found in the articles on diffraction and Fraunhofer diffraction.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] More rigorous models, involving the modelling of both electric and magnetic fields of the light wave, are required when dealing with materials whose electric and magnetic properties affect the interaction of light with the material.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] For instance, the behaviour of a light wave interacting with a metal surface is quite different from what happens when it interacts with a dielectric material.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] A vector model must also be used to model polarised light.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Numerical modeling techniques such as the finite element method, the boundary element method and the transmission-line matrix method can be used to model the propagation of light in systems which cannot be solved analytically.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Such models are computationally demanding and are normally only used to solve small-scale problems that require accuracy beyond that which can be achieved with analytical solutions.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] All of the results from geometrical optics can be recovered using the techniques of Fourier optics which apply many of the same mathematical and analytical techniques used in acoustic engineering and signal processing.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Gaussian beam propagation is a simple paraxial physical optics model for the propagation of coherent radiation such as laser beams.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] This technique partially accounts for diffraction, allowing accurate calculations of the rate at which a laser beam expands with distance, and the minimum size to which the beam can be focused.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Gaussian beam propagation thus bridges the gap between geometric and physical optics.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] In the absence of nonlinear effects, the superposition principle can be used to predict the shape of interacting waveforms through the simple addition of the disturbances.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] This interaction of waves to produce a resulting pattern is generally termed "interference" and can result in a variety of outcomes.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] If two waves of the same wavelength and frequency are *in phase*, both the wave crests and wave troughs align.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] This results in constructive interference and an increase in the amplitude of the wave, which for light is associated with a brightening of the waveform in that location.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Alternatively, if the two waves of the same wavelength and frequency are out of phase, then the wave crests will align with wave troughs and vice versa.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] This results in destructive interference and a decrease in the amplitude of the wave, which for light is associated with a dimming of the waveform at that location.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] See below for an illustration of this effect.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Interferometry is the science of measuring these patterns, usually as a means of making precise determinations of distances or angular resolutions.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] The Michelson interferometer was a famous instrument which used interference effects to accurately measure the speed of light.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] The appearance of thin films and coatings is directly affected by interference effects.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Antireflective coatings use destructive interference to reduce the reflectivity of the surfaces they coat, and can be used to minimise glare and unwanted reflections.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] The simplest case is a single layer with a thickness of one-fourth the wavelength of incident light.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] The reflected wave from the top of the film and the reflected wave from the film/material interface are then exactly 180° out of phase, causing destructive interference.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] The waves are only exactly out of phase for one wavelength, which would typically be chosen to be near the centre of the visible spectrum, around 550 nm.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] More complex designs using multiple layers can achieve low reflectivity over a broad band, or extremely low reflectivity at a single wavelength.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Constructive interference in thin films can create a strong reflection of light in a range of wavelengths, which can be narrow or broad depending on the design of the coating.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] These films are used to make dielectric mirrors, interference filters, heat reflectors, and filters for colour separation in colour television cameras.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] This interference effect is also what causes the colourful rainbow patterns seen in oil slicks.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Diffraction is the process by which light interference is most commonly observed.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] The effect was first described in 1665 by Francesco Maria Grimaldi, who also coined the term from the Latin *diffringere* 'to break into pieces'.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Later that century, Robert Hooke and Isaac Newton also described phenomena now known to be diffraction in Newton's rings while James Gregory recorded his observations of diffraction patterns from bird feathers.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] The first physical optics model of diffraction that relied on the Huygens–Fresnel principle was developed in 1803 by Thomas Young in his interference experiments with the interference patterns of two closely spaced slits.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Young showed that his results could only be explained if the two slits acted as two unique sources of waves rather than corpuscles.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] In 1815 and 1818, Augustin-Jean Fresnel firmly established the mathematics of how wave interference can account for diffraction.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] The simplest physical models of diffraction use equations that describe the angular separation of light and dark fringes due to light of a particular wavelength (λ).
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] In general, the equation takes the form $m\lambda =d\sin \theta$ where d is the separation between two wavefront sources (in the case of Young's experiments, it was two slits), θ is the angular separation between the central fringe and the m-th order fringe, where the central maximum is *m* = 0.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] This equation is modified slightly to take into account a variety of situations such as diffraction through a single gap, diffraction through multiple slits, or diffraction through a diffraction grating that contains a large number of slits at equal spacing.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] More complicated models of diffraction require working with the mathematics of Fresnel or Fraunhofer diffraction.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] X-ray diffraction makes use of the fact that atoms in a crystal have regular spacing at distances that are on the order of one angstrom.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] To see diffraction patterns, x-rays with similar wavelengths to that spacing are passed through the crystal.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Since crystals are three-dimensional objects rather than two-dimensional gratings, the associated diffraction pattern varies in two directions according to Bragg reflection, with the associated bright spots occurring in unique patterns and d being twice the spacing between atoms.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Diffraction effects limit the ability of an optical detector to optically resolve separate light sources.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] The size of such a disk is given by $\sin \theta =1.22{\frac {\lambda }{D}}$ where θ is the angular resolution, λ is the wavelength of the light, and D is the diameter of the lens aperture.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] If the angular separation of the two points is significantly less than the Airy disk angular radius, then the two points cannot be resolved in the image, but if their angular separation is much greater than this, distinct images of the two points are formed and they can therefore be resolved.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Rayleigh defined the somewhat arbitrary "Rayleigh criterion" that two points whose angular separation is equal to the Airy disk radius (measured to first null, that is, to the first place where no light is seen) can be considered to be resolved.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] It can be seen that the greater the diameter of the lens or its aperture, the finer the resolution.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Interferometry, with its ability to mimic extremely large baseline apertures, allows for the greatest angular resolution possible.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] For astronomical imaging, the atmosphere prevents optimal resolution from being achieved in the visible spectrum due to the atmospheric scattering and dispersion which cause stars to twinkle.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Astronomers refer to this effect as the quality of astronomical seeing.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Techniques known as adaptive optics have been used to eliminate the atmospheric disruption of images and achieve results that approach the diffraction limit.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Refractive processes take place in the physical optics limit, where the wavelength of light is similar to other distances, as a kind of scattering.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] The simplest type of scattering is Thomson scattering which occurs when electromagnetic waves are deflected by single particles.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] In the limit of Thomson scattering, in which the wavelike nature of light is evident, light is dispersed independent of the frequency, in contrast to Compton scattering which is frequency-dependent and strictly a quantum mechanical process, involving the nature of light as particles.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] A small proportion of light scattering from atoms or molecules may undergo Raman scattering, wherein the frequency changes due to excitation of the atoms and molecules.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Brillouin scattering occurs when the frequency of light changes due to local changes with time and movements of a dense material.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Dispersion occurs when different frequencies of light have different phase velocities, due either to material properties (*material dispersion*) or to the geometry of an optical waveguide (*waveguide dispersion*).
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] The most familiar form of dispersion is a decrease in index of refraction with increasing wavelength, which is seen in most transparent materials.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] It occurs in all dielectric materials, in wavelength ranges where the material does not absorb light.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] In wavelength ranges where a medium has significant absorption, the index of refraction can increase with wavelength.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] The separation of colours by a prism is an example of normal dispersion.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] At the surfaces of the prism, Snell's law predicts that light incident at an angle θ to the normal will be refracted at an angle arcsin(sin (*θ*) / *n*).
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Thus, blue light, with its higher refractive index, is bent more strongly than red light, resulting in the well-known rainbow pattern.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Material dispersion is often characterised by the Abbe number, which gives a simple measure of dispersion based on the index of refraction at three specific wavelengths.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Waveguide dispersion is dependent on the propagation constant.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Both kinds of dispersion cause changes in the group characteristics of the wave, the features of the wave packet that change with the same frequency as the amplitude of the electromagnetic wave.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] where n is the index of refraction and c is the speed of light in a vacuum.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] If D is less than zero, the medium is said to have *positive dispersion* or normal dispersion.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] If D is greater than zero, the medium has *negative dispersion*.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] If a light pulse is propagated through a normally dispersive medium, the result is the higher frequency components slow down more than the lower frequency components.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] The pulse therefore becomes *positively chirped*, or *up-chirped*, increasing in frequency with time.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] This causes the spectrum coming out of a prism to appear with red light the least refracted and blue/violet light the most refracted.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Conversely, if a pulse travels through an anomalously (negatively) dispersive medium, high-frequency components travel faster than the lower ones, and the pulse becomes *negatively chirped*, or *down-chirped*, decreasing in frequency with time.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] The result of group velocity dispersion, whether negative or positive, is ultimately temporal spreading of the pulse.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] This makes dispersion management extremely important in optical communications systems based on optical fibres, since if dispersion is too high, a group of pulses representing information will each spread in time and merge, making it impossible to extract the signal.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Polarisation is a general property of waves that describes the orientation of their oscillations.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] For transverse waves such as many electromagnetic waves, it describes the orientation of the oscillations in the plane perpendicular to the wave's direction of travel.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] The oscillations may be oriented in a single direction (linear polarisation), or the oscillation direction may rotate as the wave travels (circular or elliptical polarisation).
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Circularly polarised waves can rotate rightward or leftward in the direction of travel, and which of those two rotations is present in a wave is called the wave's chirality.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] The typical way to consider polarisation is to keep track of the orientation of the electric field vector as the electromagnetic wave propagates.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] The electric field vector of a plane wave may be arbitrarily divided into two perpendicular components labeled x and y (with **z** indicating the direction of travel).
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] The shape traced out in the x-y plane by the electric field vector is a Lissajous figure that describes the *polarisation state*.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] In the leftmost figure above, the x and y components of the light wave are in phase.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] In this case, the ratio of their strengths is constant, so the direction of the electric vector (the vector sum of these two components) is constant.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Since the tip of the vector traces out a single line in the plane, this special case is called linear polarisation.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] The direction of this line depends on the relative amplitudes of the two components.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] In the middle figure, the two orthogonal components have the same amplitudes and are 90° out of phase.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] In this case, one component is zero when the other component is at maximum or minimum amplitude.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] There are two possible phase relationships that satisfy this requirement: the x component can be 90° ahead of the y component or it can be 90° behind the y component.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] In this special case, the electric vector traces out a circle in the plane, so this polarisation is called circular polarisation.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] The rotation direction in the circle depends on which of the two-phase relationships exists and corresponds to *right-hand circular polarisation* and *left-hand circular polarisation*.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] In all other cases, where the two components either do not have the same amplitudes and/or their phase difference is neither zero nor a multiple of 90°, the polarisation is called elliptical polarisation because the electric vector traces out an ellipse in the plane (the *polarisation ellipse*).
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] This is shown in the above figure on the right.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Detailed mathematics of polarisation is done using Jones calculus and is characterised by the Stokes parameters.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Media that have different indexes of refraction for different polarisation modes are called *birefringent*.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Well known manifestations of this effect appear in optical wave plates/retarders (linear modes) and in Faraday rotation/optical rotation (circular modes).
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] If the path length in the birefringent medium is sufficient, plane waves will exit the material with a significantly different propagation direction, due to refraction.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] For example, this is the case with macroscopic crystals of calcite, which present the viewer with two offset, orthogonally polarised images of whatever is viewed through them.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] It was this effect that provided the first discovery of polarisation, by Erasmus Bartholinus in 1669.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] In addition, the phase shift, and thus the change in polarisation state, is usually frequency dependent, which, in combination with dichroism, often gives rise to bright colours and rainbow-like effects.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] In mineralogy, such properties, known as pleochroism, are frequently exploited for the purpose of identifying minerals using polarisation microscopes.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Additionally, many plastics that are not normally birefringent will become so when subject to mechanical stress, a phenomenon which is the basis of photoelasticity.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Non-birefringent methods, to rotate the linear polarisation of light beams, include the use of prismatic polarisation rotators which use total internal reflection in a prism set designed for efficient collinear transmission.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Media that reduce the amplitude of certain polarisation modes are called *dichroic*, with devices that block nearly all of the radiation in one mode known as *polarising filters* or simply "polarisers".
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] $I=I_{0}\cos ^{2}\theta _{\mathrm {i} },$ where *I*0 is the initial intensity, and *θ*i is the angle between the light's initial polarisation direction and the axis of the polariser.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] A beam of unpolarised light can be thought of as containing a uniform mixture of linear polarisations at all possible angles.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] In practice, some light is lost in the polariser and the actual transmission of unpolarised light will be somewhat lower than this, around 38% for Polaroid-type polarisers but considerably higher (>49.9%) for some birefringent prism types.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] In addition to birefringence and dichroism in extended media, polarisation effects can also occur at the (reflective) interface between two materials of different refractive index.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] These effects are treated by the Fresnel equations.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Part of the wave is transmitted and part is reflected, with the ratio depending on the angle of incidence and the angle of refraction.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] In this way, physical optics recovers Brewster's angle.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] When light reflects from a thin film on a surface, interference between the reflections from the film's surfaces can produce polarisation in the reflected and transmitted light.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Most sources of electromagnetic radiation contain a large number of atoms or molecules that emit light.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] The orientation of the electric fields produced by these emitters may not be correlated, in which case the light is said to be *unpolarised*.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] If there is partial correlation between the emitters, the light is *partially polarised*.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] If the polarisation is consistent across the spectrum of the source, partially polarised light can be described as a superposition of a completely unpolarised component, and a completely polarised one.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] One may then describe the light in terms of the degree of polarisation, and the parameters of the polarisation ellipse.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Light reflected by shiny transparent materials is partly or fully polarised, except when the light is normal (perpendicular) to the surface.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] It was this effect that allowed the mathematician Étienne-Louis Malus to make the measurements that allowed for his development of the first mathematical models for polarised light.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Polarisation occurs when light is scattered in the atmosphere.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] The scattered light produces the brightness and colour in clear skies.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] This partial polarisation of scattered light can be taken advantage of using polarising filters to darken the sky in photographs.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p01] Optical polarisation is principally of importance in chemistry due to circular dichroism and optical rotation (*circular birefringence*) exhibited by optically active (chiral) molecules.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Specialty areas of optics research include the study of how light interacts with specific materials as in crystal optics and metamaterials.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Other research focuses on the phenomenology of electromagnetic waves as in singular optics, non-imaging optics, non-linear optics, statistical optics, and radiometry.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Additionally, computer engineers have taken an interest in integrated optics, machine vision, and photonic computing as possible components of the "next generation" of computers.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Today, the pure science of optics is called optical science or optical physics to distinguish it from applied optical sciences, which are referred to as optical engineering.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Prominent subfields of optical engineering include illumination engineering, photonics, and optoelectronics with practical applications like lens design, fabrication and testing of optical components, and image processing.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Some of these fields overlap, with nebulous boundaries between the subjects' terms that mean slightly different things in different parts of the world and in different areas of industry.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] A professional community of researchers in nonlinear optics has developed in the last several decades due to advances in laser technology.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] A laser is a device that emits light, a kind of electromagnetic radiation, through a process called *stimulated emission*.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] The term *laser* is an acronym for 'Light Amplification by Stimulated Emission of Radiation'.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Laser light is usually spatially coherent, which means that the light either is emitted in a narrow, low-divergence beam, or can be converted into one with the help of optical components such as lenses.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Because the microwave equivalent of the laser, the *maser*, was developed first, devices that emit microwave and radio frequencies are usually called *masers*.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] The first working laser was demonstrated on 16 May 1960 by Theodore Maiman at Hughes Research Laboratories.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] When first invented, they were called "a solution looking for a problem".
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Since then, lasers have become a multibillion-dollar industry, finding utility in thousands of highly varied applications.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] The first application of lasers visible in the daily lives of the general population was the supermarket barcode scanner, introduced in 1974.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] The laserdisc player, introduced in 1978, was the first successful consumer product to include a laser, but the compact disc player was the first laser-equipped device to become truly common in consumers' homes, beginning in 1982.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] These optical storage devices use a semiconductor laser less than a millimetre wide to scan the surface of the disc for data retrieval.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Fibre-optic communication relies on lasers to transmit large amounts of information at the speed of light.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Other common applications of lasers include laser printers and laser pointers.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Lasers are used in medicine in areas such as bloodless surgery, laser eye surgery, and laser capture microdissection and in military applications such as missile defence systems, electro-optical countermeasures (EOCM), and lidar.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Lasers are also used in holograms, bubblegrams, laser light shows, and laser hair removal.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] The Kapitsa–Dirac effect causes beams of particles to diffract as the result of meeting a standing wave of light.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Light can be used to position matter using various phenomena (see optical tweezers).
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] The ubiquity of visual systems in biology indicates the central role optics plays as the science of one of the five senses.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Many people benefit from eyeglasses or contact lenses, and optics are integral to the functioning of many consumer goods including cameras.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Rainbows and mirages are examples of optical phenomena.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Optical communication provides the backbone for both the Internet and modern telephony.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] The human eye functions by focusing light onto a layer of photoreceptor cells called the retina, which forms the inner lining of the back of the eye.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] The focusing is accomplished by a series of transparent media.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Light entering the eye passes first through the cornea, which provides much of the eye's optical power.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] The light then continues through the fluid just behind the cornea—the anterior chamber, then passes through the pupil.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] The light then passes through the lens, which focuses the light further and allows adjustment of focus.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] The light then passes through the main body of fluid in the eye—the vitreous humour, and reaches the retina.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] The cells in the retina line the back of the eye, except for where the optic nerve exits; this results in a blind spot.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] There are two types of photoreceptor cells, rods and cones, which are sensitive to different aspects of light.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Rod cells are sensitive to the intensity of light over a wide frequency range, thus are responsible for black-and-white vision.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Rod cells are not present on the fovea, the area of the retina responsible for central vision, and are not as responsive as cone cells to spatial and temporal changes in light.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] There are, however, twenty times more rod cells than cone cells in the retina because the rod cells are present across a wider area.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Because of their wider distribution, rods are responsible for peripheral vision.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] In contrast, cone cells are less sensitive to the overall intensity of light, but come in three varieties that are sensitive to different frequency-ranges and thus are used in the perception of colour and photopic vision.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Cone cells are highly concentrated in the fovea and have a high visual acuity meaning that they are better at spatial resolution than rod cells.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Since cone cells are not as sensitive to dim light as rod cells, most night vision is limited to rod cells.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Likewise, since cone cells are in the fovea, central vision (including the vision needed to do most reading, fine detail work such as sewing, or careful examination of objects) is done by cone cells.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Ciliary muscles around the lens allow the eye's focus to be adjusted.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] The near point and far point define the nearest and farthest distances from the eye at which an object can be brought into sharp focus.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] For a person with normal vision, the far point is located at infinity.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] The near point's location depends on how much the muscles can increase the curvature of the lens, and how inflexible the lens has become with age.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Optometrists, ophthalmologists, and opticians usually consider an appropriate near point to be closer than normal reading distance—approximately 25 cm.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Defects in vision can be explained using optical principles.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] As people age, the lens becomes less flexible and the near point recedes from the eye, a condition known as presbyopia.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Similarly, people suffering from hyperopia cannot decrease the focal length of their lens enough to allow for nearby objects to be imaged on their retina.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Conversely, people who cannot increase the focal length of their lens enough to allow for distant objects to be imaged on the retina suffer from myopia and have a far point that is considerably closer than infinity.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] A condition known as astigmatism results when the cornea is not spherical but instead is more curved in one direction.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] This causes horizontally extended objects to be focused on different parts of the retina than vertically extended objects, and results in distorted images.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] All of these conditions can be corrected using corrective lenses.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] For presbyopia and hyperopia, a converging lens provides the extra curvature necessary to bring the near point closer to the eye while for myopia a diverging lens provides the curvature necessary to send the far point to infinity.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Astigmatism is corrected with a cylindrical surface lens that curves more strongly in one direction than in another, compensating for the non-uniformity of the cornea.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] The optical power of corrective lenses is measured in diopters, a value equal to the reciprocal of the focal length measured in metres; with a positive focal length corresponding to a converging lens and a negative focal length corresponding to a diverging lens.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] For lenses that correct for astigmatism as well, three numbers are given: one for the spherical power, one for the cylindrical power, and one for the angle of orientation of the astigmatism.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Optical illusions (also called visual illusions) are characterized by visually perceived images that differ from objective reality.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] The information gathered by the eye is processed in the brain to give a percept that differs from the object being imaged.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Cognitive illusions include some which result from the unconscious misapplication of certain optical principles.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] This suggestion is also responsible for the famous moon illusion where the moon, despite having essentially the same angular size, appears much larger near the horizon than it does at zenith.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] This illusion so confounded Ptolemy that he incorrectly attributed it to atmospheric refraction when he described it in his treatise, *Optics*.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Another type of optical illusion exploits broken patterns to trick the mind into perceiving symmetries or asymmetries that are not present.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Examples include the café wall, Ehrenstein, Fraser spiral, Poggendorff, and Zöllner illusions.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Related, but not strictly illusions, are patterns that occur due to the superimposition of periodic structures.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] For example, transparent tissues with a grid structure produce shapes known as moiré patterns, while the superimposition of periodic transparent patterns comprising parallel opaque lines or curves produces line moiré patterns.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Single lenses have a variety of applications including photographic lenses, corrective lenses, and magnifying glasses while single mirrors are used in parabolic reflectors and rear-view mirrors.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Combining a number of mirrors, prisms, and lenses produces compound optical instruments which have practical uses.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] For example, a periscope is simply two plane mirrors aligned to allow for viewing around obstructions.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] The most famous compound optical instruments in science are the microscope and the telescope which were both invented by the Dutch in the late 16th century.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Microscopes were first developed with just two lenses: an objective lens and an eyepiece.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] The objective lens is essentially a magnifying glass and was designed with a very small focal length while the eyepiece generally has a longer focal length.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] This has the effect of producing magnified images of close objects.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Generally, an additional source of illumination is used since magnified images are dimmer due to the conservation of energy and the spreading of light rays over a larger surface area.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Modern microscopes, known as *compound microscopes* have many lenses in them (typically four) to optimize the functionality and enhance image stability.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] A slightly different variety of microscope, the comparison microscope, looks at side-by-side images to produce a stereoscopic binocular view that appears three dimensional when used by humans.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] The first telescopes, called refracting telescopes, were also developed with a single objective and eyepiece lens.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] In contrast to the microscope, the objective lens of the telescope was designed with a large focal length to avoid optical aberrations.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] The objective focuses an image of a distant object at its focal point which is adjusted to be at the focal point of an eyepiece of a much smaller focal length.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] The main goal of a telescope is not necessarily magnification, but rather the collection of light which is determined by the physical size of the objective lens.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Thus, telescopes are normally indicated by the diameters of their objectives rather than by the magnification which can be changed by switching eyepieces.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Because the magnification of a telescope is equal to the focal length of the objective divided by the focal length of the eyepiece, smaller focal-length eyepieces cause greater magnification.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Since crafting large lenses is much more difficult than crafting large mirrors, most modern telescopes are *reflecting telescopes*, that is, telescopes that use a primary mirror rather than an objective lens.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] The same general optical considerations apply to reflecting telescopes that applied to refracting telescopes, namely, the larger the primary mirror, the more light collected, and the magnification is still equal to the focal length of the primary mirror divided by the focal length of the eyepiece.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Professional telescopes generally do not have eyepieces and instead place an instrument (often a charge-coupled device) at the focal point instead.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] The optics of photography involves both lenses and the medium in which the electromagnetic radiation is recorded, whether it be a plate, film, or charge-coupled device.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] In other words, the smaller the aperture (giving greater depth of focus), the less light coming in, so the length of time has to be increased (leading to possible blurriness if motion occurs).
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] An example of the use of the law of reciprocity is the Sunny 16 rule which gives a rough estimate for the settings needed to estimate the proper exposure in daylight.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] where f is the focal length, and D is the diameter of the entrance pupil.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] By convention, "f/#" is treated as a single symbol, and specific values of f/# are written by replacing the number sign with the value.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] The two ways to increase the f-stop are to either decrease the diameter of the entrance pupil or change to a longer focal length (in the case of a zoom lens, this can be done by simply adjusting the lens).
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Higher f-numbers also have a larger depth of field due to the lens approaching the limit of a pinhole camera which is able to focus all images perfectly, regardless of distance, but requires very long exposure times.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] The field of view that the lens will provide changes with the focal length of the lens.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Modern zoom lenses may have some or all of these attributes.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] The required exposure time depends on how sensitive to light the medium being used is (measured by the film speed, or, for digital media, by the quantum efficiency).
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Early photography used media that had very low light sensitivity, and so exposure times had to be long even for very bright shots.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] As technology has improved, so has the sensitivity through film cameras and digital cameras.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Other results from physical and geometrical optics apply to camera optics.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] For example, the maximum resolution capability of a particular camera set-up is determined by the diffraction limit associated with the pupil size and given, roughly, by the Rayleigh criterion.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] The unique optical properties of the atmosphere cause a wide range of spectacular optical phenomena.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] The blue colour of the sky is a direct result of Rayleigh scattering which redirects higher frequency (blue) sunlight back into the field of view of the observer.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Because blue light is scattered more easily than red light, the sun takes on a reddish hue when it is observed through a thick atmosphere, as during a sunrise or sunset.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Additional particulate matter in the sky can scatter different colours at different angles creating colourful glowing skies at dusk and dawn.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Scattering off of ice crystals and other particles in the atmosphere are responsible for halos, afterglows, coronas, rays of sunlight, and sun dogs.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] The variation in these kinds of phenomena is due to different particle sizes and geometries.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Mirages are optical phenomena in which light rays are bent due to thermal variations in the refraction index of air, producing displaced or heavily distorted images of distant objects.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Other dramatic optical phenomena associated with this include the Novaya Zemlya effect where the sun appears to rise earlier than predicted with a distorted shape.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] A spectacular form of refraction occurs with a temperature inversion called the Fata Morgana where objects on the horizon or even beyond the horizon, such as islands, cliffs, ships or icebergs, appear elongated and elevated, like "fairy tale castles".
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Rainbows are the result of a combination of internal reflection and dispersive refraction of light in raindrops.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] A single reflection off the backs of an array of raindrops produces a rainbow with an angular size on the sky that ranges from 40° to 42° with red on the outside.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Double rainbows are produced by two internal reflections with angular size of 50.5° to 54° with violet on the outside.
[src:optics-physics/optics-p02] Because rainbows are seen with the sun 180° away from the centre of the rainbow, rainbows are more prominent the closer the sun is to the horizon.
[src:optics-physics/physical-optics] In physics, **physical optics**, or **wave optics**, is the branch of optics that studies interference, diffraction, polarization, and other phenomena for which the ray approximation of geometric optics is not valid.
[src:optics-physics/physical-optics] This usage tends not to include effects such as quantum noise in optical communication, which is studied in the sub-branch of coherence theory.
[src:optics-physics/physical-optics] This approximation consists of using ray optics to estimate the field on a surface and then integrating that field over the surface to calculate the transmitted or scattered field.
[src:optics-physics/physical-optics] This resembles the Born approximation, in that the details of the problem are treated as a perturbation.
[src:optics-physics/physical-optics] In optics, it is a standard way of estimating diffraction effects.
[src:optics-physics/physical-optics] In radio, this approximation is used to estimate some effects that resemble optical effects.
[src:optics-physics/physical-optics] It models several interference, diffraction and polarization effects but not the dependence of diffraction on polarization.
[src:optics-physics/physical-optics] Since this is a high-frequency approximation, it is often more accurate in optics than for radio.
[src:optics-physics/physical-optics] In optics, it typically consists of integrating ray-estimated field over a lens, mirror or aperture to calculate the transmitted or scattered field.
[src:optics-physics/physical-optics] In radar scattering it usually means taking the current that would be found on a tangent plane of similar material as the current at each point on the front, i. e. the geometrically illuminated part, of a scatterer.
[src:optics-physics/physical-optics] Current on the shadowed parts is taken as zero.
[src:optics-physics/physical-optics] The approximate scattered field is then obtained by an integral over these approximate currents.
[src:optics-physics/physical-optics] This is useful for bodies with large smooth convex shapes and for lossy (low-reflection) surfaces.
[src:optics-physics/physical-optics] The ray-optics field or current is generally not accurate near edges or shadow boundaries, unless supplemented by diffraction and creeping wave calculations.
[src:optics-physics/physical-optics] The standard theory of physical optics has some defects in the evaluation of scattered fields, leading to decreased accuracy away from the specular direction.
[src:optics-physics/physical-optics] An improved theory introduced in 2004 gives exact solutions to problems involving wave diffraction by conducting scatterers.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] An electromagnetic wave such as light consists of a coupled oscillating electric field and magnetic field that are always perpendicular to each other.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Different states of polarization correspond to different relationships between the directions of the fields and the direction of propagation.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] In linear polarization, the electric and magnetic fields each oscillate in a single direction, perpendicular to one another.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] In circular or elliptical polarization, the fields rotate around the beam's direction of travel at a constant rate.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] The rotation can be either in the right-hand or in the left-hand direction.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Light or other electromagnetic radiation from many sources, such as the sun, flames, and incandescent lamps, consists of short wave trains with an equal mixture of polarizations; this is called *unpolarized light*.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Polarized light can be produced by passing unpolarized light through a polarizer, which allows waves of only one polarization to pass through.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] The most common optical materials do not affect the polarization of light, but some materials—those that exhibit birefringence, dichroism, or optical activity—affect light differently depending on its polarization.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Some of these are used to make polarizing filters.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Light also becomes partially polarized when it reflects at an angle from a surface.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] According to quantum mechanics, electromagnetic waves can also be viewed as streams of particles called photons.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] When viewed in this way, the polarization of an electromagnetic wave is determined by a quantum mechanical property of photons called their spin.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] A photon has one of two possible spins: it can either spin in a right hand sense or a left hand sense about its direction of travel.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Circularly polarized electromagnetic waves are composed of photons with only one type of spin, either right- or left-hand.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Linearly polarized waves consist of photons that are in a superposition of right and left circularly polarized states, with equal amplitude and phases synchronized to give oscillation in a plane.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Polarization is an important parameter in areas of science dealing with transverse waves, such as optics, seismology, radio, and microwaves.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Especially impacted are technologies such as lasers, wireless and optical fiber telecommunications, and radar.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Most sources of light are classified as incoherent and unpolarized (or only "partially polarized") because they consist of a random mixture of waves having different spatial characteristics, frequencies (wavelengths), phases, and polarization states.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] However, for understanding electromagnetic waves and polarization in particular, it is easier to just consider coherent plane waves; these are sinusoidal waves of one particular direction (or wavevector), frequency, phase, and polarization state.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Characterizing an optical system in relation to a plane wave with those given parameters can then be used to predict its response to a more general case, since a wave with any specified spatial structure can be decomposed into a combination of plane waves (its so-called angular spectrum).
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Incoherent states can be modeled stochastically as a weighted combination of such uncorrelated waves with some distribution of frequencies (its *spectrum*), phases, and polarizations.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] By convention, the "polarization" direction of an electromagnetic wave is given by its electric field vector.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Considering a monochromatic plane wave of optical frequency f (light of vacuum wavelength λ has a frequency of *f* = *c/λ* where c is the speed of light), let us take the direction of propagation as the z axis.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Being a transverse wave the **E** and **H** fields must then contain components only in the x and y directions whereas *Ez* = *Hz* = 0.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Using complex (or phasor) notation, the instantaneous physical electric and magnetic fields are given by the real parts of the complex quantities occurring in the following equations.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Here ex, ey, hx, and hy are complex numbers.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] In the second more compact form, as these equations are customarily expressed, these factors are described using the wavenumber *k* = 2π*n*/*λ*0 and angular frequency (or "radian frequency") *ω* = 2π*f*.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] In a more general formulation with propagation *not* restricted to the *+z* direction, then the spatial dependence *kz* is replaced by *k*→ ∙ *r*→ where k→ is called the wave vector, the magnitude of which is the wavenumber.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Thus the leading vectors **e** and **h** each contain up to two nonzero (complex) components describing the amplitude and phase of the wave's x and y polarization components (again, there can be no z polarization component for a transverse wave in the +*z* direction).
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] In a dielectric, η is real and has the value *η*0/*n*, where n is the refractive index and *η*0 is the impedance of free space.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] The impedance will be complex in a conducting medium.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Knowing the propagation direction (+*z* in this case) and η, one can just as well specify the wave in terms of just ex and ey describing the electric field.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] The vector containing ex and ey (but without the z component which is necessarily zero for a transverse wave) is known as a Jones vector.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] In addition to specifying the polarization state of the wave, a general Jones vector also specifies the overall magnitude and phase of that wave.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] However, the wave's *state of polarization* is only dependent on the (complex) ratio of ey to ex.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] So let us just consider waves whose |*ex*|2 + |*ey*|2 = 1; this happens to correspond to an intensity of about 0.00133 W/m2 in free space (where *η* = *η*0).
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] And because the absolute phase of a wave is unimportant in discussing its polarization state, let us stipulate that the phase of ex is zero; in other words ex is a real number while ey may be complex.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] In addition to transverse waves, there are many wave motions where the oscillation is not limited to directions perpendicular to the direction of propagation.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] These cases are far beyond the scope of the current article, which concentrates on transverse waves (such as most electromagnetic waves in bulk media), but one should be aware of cases where the polarization of a coherent wave cannot be described simply using a Jones vector, as we have just done.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] In those cases the electric displacement **D** and magnetic flux density **B** still obey the above geometry but due to anisotropy in the electric susceptibility (or in the magnetic permeability), now given by a tensor, the direction of **E** (or **H**) may differ from that of **D** (or **B**).
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Even in isotropic media, so-called inhomogeneous waves can be launched into a medium whose refractive index has a significant imaginary part (or "extinction coefficient") such as metals; these fields are also not strictly transverse.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Surface waves or waves propagating in a waveguide (such as an optical fiber) are generally *not* transverse waves, but might be described as an electric or magnetic transverse mode, or a hybrid mode.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Even in free space, longitudinal field components can be generated in focal regions, where the plane wave approximation breaks down.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] An extreme example is radially or tangentially polarized light, at the focus of which the electric or magnetic field respectively is *entirely* longitudinal (along the direction of propagation).
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] For longitudinal waves such as sound waves in fluids, the direction of oscillation is by definition along the direction of travel, so the issue of polarization is normally not even mentioned.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] On the other hand, sound waves in a bulk solid can be transverse as well as longitudinal, for a total of three polarization components.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] In this case, the transverse polarization is associated with the direction of the shear stress and displacement in directions perpendicular to the propagation direction, while the longitudinal polarization describes compression of the solid and vibration along the direction of propagation.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] The differential propagation of transverse and longitudinal polarizations is important in seismology.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Polarization can be defined in terms of pure polarization states with only a coherent sinusoidal wave at one optical frequency.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] The vector in the adjacent diagram might describe the oscillation of the electric field emitted by a single-mode laser (whose oscillation frequency would be typically 1015 times faster).
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] The field oscillates in the xy-plane, along the page, with the wave propagating in the z direction, perpendicular to the page.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] The first two diagrams below trace the electric field vector over a complete cycle for linear polarization at two different orientations; these are each considered a distinct *state of polarization* (SOP).
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] The linear polarization at 45° can also be viewed as the addition of a horizontally linearly polarized wave (as in the leftmost figure) and a vertically polarized wave of the same amplitude *in the same phase*.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Now if one were to introduce a phase shift in between those horizontal and vertical polarization components, one would generally obtain elliptical polarization as is shown in the third figure.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] When the phase shift is exactly ±90°, and the amplitudes are the same, then **circular polarization** is produced (fourth and fifth figures).
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Circular polarization can be created by sending linearly polarized light through a quarter-wave plate oriented at 45° to the linear polarization to create two components of the same amplitude with the required phase shift.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] The superposition of the original and phase-shifted components causes a rotating electric field vector, which is depicted in the animation on the right.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Note that circular or elliptical polarization can involve either a clockwise or counterclockwise rotation of the field, depending on the relative phases of the components.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] These correspond to distinct polarization states, such as the two circular polarizations shown above.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] The orientation of the x and y axes used in this description is arbitrary.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] The choice of such a coordinate system and viewing the polarization ellipse in terms of the x and y polarization components, corresponds to the definition of the Jones vector (below) in terms of those basis polarizations.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Axes are selected to suit a particular problem, such as x being in the plane of incidence.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Since there are separate reflection coefficients for the linear polarizations in and orthogonal to the plane of incidence (*p* and *s* polarizations, see below), that choice greatly simplifies the calculation of a wave's reflection from a surface.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Any pair of orthogonal polarization states may be used as basis functions, not just linear polarizations.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] For instance, choosing right and left circular polarizations as basis functions simplifies the solution of problems involving circular birefringence (optical activity) or circular dichroism.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] For a purely polarized monochromatic wave the electric field vector over one cycle of oscillation traces out an ellipse.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] A polarization state can then be described in relation to the geometrical parameters of the ellipse, and its "handedness", that is, whether the rotation around the ellipse is clockwise or counter clockwise.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] One parameterization of the elliptical figure specifies the **orientation angle** ψ, defined as the angle between the major axis of the ellipse and the x-axis along with the **ellipticity** *ε* = *a/b*, the ratio of the ellipse's major to minor axis.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] The ellipticity parameter is an alternative parameterization of an ellipse's eccentricity ${\textstyle e={\sqrt {1-b^{2}/a^{2}}},}$ or the **ellipticity angle**, ${\textstyle \chi =\arctan b/a}$ ${\textstyle =\arctan 1/\varepsilon }$ as is shown in the figure.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] The angle χ is also significant in that the latitude (angle from the equator) of the polarization state as represented on the Poincaré sphere (see below) is equal to ±2*χ*.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] The special cases of linear and circular polarization correspond to an ellipticity ε of infinity and unity (or χ of zero and 45°) respectively.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Full information on a completely polarized state is also provided by the amplitude and phase of oscillations in two components of the electric field vector in the plane of polarization.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] This representation was used above to show how different states of polarization are possible.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Here *a*1 and *a*2 denote the amplitude of the wave in the two components of the electric field vector, while *θ*1 and *θ*2 represent the phases.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] The product of a Jones vector with a complex number of unit modulus gives a different Jones vector representing the same ellipse, and thus the same state of polarization.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] The physical electric field, as the real part of the Jones vector, would be altered but the polarization state itself is independent of absolute phase.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] The basis vectors used to represent the Jones vector need not represent linear polarization states (i.e. be real).
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] In general any two orthogonal states can be used, where an orthogonal vector pair is formally defined as one having a zero inner product.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] A common choice is left and right circular polarizations, for example to model the different propagation of waves in two such components in circularly birefringent media (see below) or signal paths of coherent detectors sensitive to circular polarization.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Regardless of whether polarization state is represented using geometric parameters or Jones vectors, implicit in the parameterization is the orientation of the coordinate frame.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] This permits a degree of freedom, namely rotation about the propagation direction.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] When considering light that is propagating parallel to the surface of the Earth, the terms "horizontal" and "vertical" polarization are often used, with the former being associated with the first component of the Jones vector, or zero azimuth angle.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] On the other hand, in astronomy the equatorial coordinate system is generally used instead, with the zero azimuth (or position angle, as it is more commonly called in astronomy to avoid confusion with the horizontal coordinate system) corresponding to due north.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Another coordinate system frequently used relates to the *plane of incidence*.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] This is the plane made by the incoming propagation direction and the vector perpendicular to the plane of an interface, in other words, the plane in which the ray travels before and after reflection or refraction.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] The component of the electric field parallel to this plane is termed *p-like* (parallel) and the component perpendicular to this plane is termed *s-like* (from *senkrecht*, German for 'perpendicular').
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Polarized light with its electric field along the plane of incidence is thus denoted **p-polarized**, while light whose electric field is normal to the plane of incidence is called **s-polarized**.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] *P*-polarization is commonly referred to as *transverse-magnetic* (TM), and has also been termed *pi-polarized* or *π-polarized*, or *tangential plane polarized*.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] *S*-polarization is also called *transverse-electric* (TE), as well as *sigma-polarized* or *σ-polarized*, or *sagittal plane polarized*.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] DOP can be used to map the strain field in materials when considering the DOP of the photoluminescence.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] The polarization of the photoluminescence is related to the strain in a material by way of the given material's photoelasticity tensor.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] DOP is also visualized using the Poincaré sphere representation of a polarized beam.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] In this representation, DOP is equal to the length of the vector measured from the center of the sphere.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Unpolarized light is light with a random, time-varying polarization.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Natural light, like most other common sources of visible light, is produced independently by a large number of atoms or molecules whose emissions are uncorrelated.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Unpolarized light can be produced from the incoherent combination of vertical and horizontal linearly polarized light, or right- and left-handed circularly polarized light.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Conversely, the two constituent linearly polarized states of unpolarized light cannot form an interference pattern, even if rotated into alignment (Fresnel–Arago 3rd law).
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] A so-called *depolarizer* acts on a polarized beam to create one in which the polarization varies so rapidly across the beam that it may be ignored in the intended applications.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Conversely, a *polarizer* acts on an unpolarized beam or arbitrarily polarized beam to create one which is polarized.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Unpolarized light can be described as a mixture of two independent oppositely polarized streams, each with half the intensity.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Light is said to be *partially polarized* when there is more power in one of these streams than the other.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] At any particular wavelength, partially polarized light can be statistically described as the superposition of a completely unpolarized component and a completely polarized one.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] One may then describe the light in terms of the degree of polarization and the parameters of the polarized component.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] That polarized component can be described in terms of a Jones vector or polarization ellipse.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] However, in order to also describe the degree of polarization, one normally employs Stokes parameters to specify a state of partial polarization.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] In a vacuum, the components of the electric field propagate at the speed of light, so that the phase of the wave varies in space and time while the polarization state does not.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] As noted above, the instantaneous electric field is the real part of the product of the Jones vector times the phase factor $e^{-i\omega t}$ .
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] When an electromagnetic wave interacts with matter, its propagation is altered according to the material's (complex) index of refraction.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] When the real or imaginary part of that refractive index is dependent on the polarization state of a wave, properties known as birefringence and polarization dichroism (or diattenuation) respectively, then the polarization state of a wave will generally be altered.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] In such media, an electromagnetic wave with any given state of polarization may be decomposed into two orthogonally polarized components that encounter different propagation constants.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] The Jones matrix due to passage through a transparent material is dependent on the propagation distance as well as the birefringence.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] The birefringence (as well as the average refractive index) will generally be dispersive, that is, it will vary as a function of optical frequency (wavelength).
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] In the case of non-birefringent materials, however, the 2 × 2 Jones matrix is the identity matrix (multiplied by a scalar phase factor and attenuation factor), implying no change in polarization during propagation.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] where *g*1 and *g*2 are complex numbers describing the phase delay and possibly the amplitude attenuation due to propagation in each of the two polarization eigenmodes.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] In a birefringent substance, electromagnetic waves of different polarizations travel at different speeds (phase velocities).
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] As a result, when unpolarized waves travel through a plate of birefringent material, one polarization component has a shorter wavelength than the other, resulting in a phase difference between the components which increases the further the waves travel through the material.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] The Jones matrix is a unitary matrix: |*g*1| = |*g*2| = 1.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Media termed diattenuating (or *dichroic* in the sense of polarization), in which only the amplitudes of the two polarizations are affected differentially, may be described using a Hermitian matrix (generally multiplied by a common phase factor).
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] In fact, since *any* matrix may be written as the product of unitary and positive Hermitian matrices, light propagation through any sequence of polarization-dependent optical components can be written as the product of these two basic types of transformations.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] In birefringent media there is no attenuation, but two modes accrue a differential phase delay.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Well known manifestations of linear birefringence (that is, in which the basis polarizations are orthogonal linear polarizations) appear in optical wave plates/retarders and many crystals.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] If linearly polarized light passes through a birefringent material, its state of polarization will generally change, *unless* its polarization direction is identical to one of those basis polarizations.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Since the phase shift, and thus the change in polarization state, is usually wavelength-dependent, such objects viewed under white light in between two polarizers may give rise to colorful effects, as seen in the accompanying photograph.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Circular birefringence is also termed optical activity, especially in chiral fluids, or Faraday rotation, when due to the presence of a magnetic field along the direction of propagation.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] When linearly polarized light is passed through such an object, it will exit still linearly polarized, but with the axis of polarization rotated.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] A combination of linear and circular birefringence will have as basis polarizations two orthogonal elliptical polarizations; however, the term "elliptical birefringence" is rarely used.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] One can visualize the case of linear birefringence (with two orthogonal linear propagation modes) with an incoming wave linearly polarized at a 45° angle to those modes.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] In general the situation is more complicated and can be characterized as a rotation in the Poincaré sphere about the axis defined by the propagation modes.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Examples for linear (blue), circular (red), and elliptical (yellow) birefringence are shown in the figure on the left.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] The total intensity and degree of polarization are unaffected.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] If the path length in the birefringent medium is sufficient, the two polarization components of a collimated beam (or ray) can exit the material with a positional offset, even though their final propagation directions will be the same (assuming the entrance face and exit face are parallel).
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] This is commonly viewed using calcite crystals, which present the viewer with two slightly offset images, in opposite polarizations, of an object behind the crystal.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] It was this effect that provided the first discovery of polarization, by Erasmus Bartholinus in 1669.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Media in which transmission of one polarization mode is preferentially reduced are called *dichroic* or *diattenuating*.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Like birefringence, diattenuation can be with respect to linear polarization modes (in a crystal) or circular polarization modes (usually in a liquid).
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Devices that block nearly all of the radiation in one mode are known as **polarizing filters** or simply "polarizers".
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] This corresponds to *g*2 = 0 in the above representation of the Jones matrix.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] The output of an ideal polarizer is a specific polarization state (usually linear polarization) with an amplitude equal to the input wave's original amplitude in that polarization mode.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Power in the other polarization mode is eliminated.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Thus if unpolarized light is passed through an ideal polarizer (where *g*1 = 1 and *g*2 = 0) exactly half of its initial power is retained.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Practical polarizers, especially inexpensive sheet polarizers, have additional loss so that *g*1 < 1.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] However, in many instances the more relevant figure of merit is the polarizer's degree of polarization or extinction ratio, which involve a comparison of *g*1 to *g*2.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Since Jones vectors refer to waves' amplitudes (rather than intensity), when illuminated by unpolarized light the remaining power in the unwanted polarization will be (*g*2/*g*1)2 of the power in the intended polarization.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] In addition to birefringence and dichroism in extended media, polarization effects describable using Jones matrices can also occur at (reflective) interface between two materials of different refractive index.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Part of the wave is transmitted and part is reflected; for a given material those proportions (and also the phase of reflection) are dependent on the angle of incidence and are different for the *s*- and *p*-polarizations.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Therefore, the polarization state of reflected light (even if initially unpolarized) is generally changed.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Any light striking a surface at a special angle of incidence known as Brewster's angle, where the reflection coefficient for *p*-polarization is zero, will be reflected with only the *s*-polarization remaining.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] This principle is employed in the so-called "pile of plates polarizer" (see figure) in which part of the *s*-polarization is removed by reflection at each Brewster angle surface, leaving only the *p*-polarization after transmission through many such surfaces.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] The generally smaller reflection coefficient of the *p*-polarization is also the basis of polarized sunglasses; by blocking the *s*- (horizontal) polarization, most of the glare due to reflection from a wet street, for instance, is removed.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] In the important special case of reflection at normal incidence (not involving anisotropic materials) there is no particular *s*- or *p*-polarization.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Both the x and y polarization components are reflected identically, and therefore the polarization of the reflected wave is identical to that of the incident wave.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] However, in the case of circular (or elliptical) polarization, the handedness of the polarization state is thereby reversed, since by convention this is specified relative to the direction of propagation.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] The circular rotation of the electric field around the *x-y* axes called "right-handed" for a wave in the +*z* direction is "left-handed" for a wave in the −*z* direction.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] But in the general case of reflection at a nonzero angle of incidence, no such generalization can be made.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] For instance, right-circularly polarized light reflected from a dielectric surface at a grazing angle, will still be right-handed (but elliptically) polarized.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Linear polarized light reflected from a metal at non-normal incidence will generally become elliptically polarized.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] These cases are handled using Jones vectors acted upon by the different Fresnel coefficients for the *s*- and *p*-polarization components.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Some optical measurement techniques are based on polarization.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] In many other optical techniques polarization is crucial or at least must be taken into account and controlled; such examples are too numerous to mention.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] In engineering, the phenomenon of stress induced birefringence allows for stresses in transparent materials to be readily observed.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] As noted above and seen in the accompanying photograph, the chromaticity of birefringence typically creates colored patterns when viewed in between two polarizers.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] As external forces are applied, internal stress induced in the material is thereby observed.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Additionally, birefringence is frequently observed due to stresses "frozen in" at the time of manufacture.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] This is famously observed in cellophane tape whose birefringence is due to the stretching of the material during the manufacturing process.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Ellipsometry is a powerful technique for the measurement of the optical properties of a uniform surface.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] It involves measuring the polarization state of light following specular reflection from such a surface.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] This is typically done as a function of incidence angle or wavelength (or both).
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Since ellipsometry relies on reflection, it is not required for the sample to be transparent to light or for its back side to be accessible.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Ellipsometry can be used to model the (complex) refractive index of a surface of a bulk material.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] It is also very useful in determining parameters of one or more thin film layers deposited on a substrate.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Due to their reflection properties, not only are the predicted magnitude of the *p* and *s* polarization components, but their relative phase shifts upon reflection, compared to measurements using an ellipsometer.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] In addition to use in science and research, ellipsometers are used in situ to control production processes for instance.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] The property of (linear) birefringence is widespread in crystalline minerals, and indeed was pivotal in the initial discovery of polarization.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] In mineralogy, this property is frequently exploited using polarization microscopes, for the purpose of identifying minerals.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] See optical mineralogy for more details.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Sound waves in solid materials exhibit polarization.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Differential propagation of the three polarizations through the earth is a crucial in the field of seismology.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Horizontally and vertically polarized seismic waves (shear waves) are termed SH and SV, while waves with longitudinal polarization (compressional waves) are termed P-waves.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] We have seen (above) that the birefringence of a type of crystal is useful in identifying it, and thus detection of linear birefringence is especially useful in geology and mineralogy.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Linearly polarized light generally has its polarization state altered upon transmission through such a crystal, making it stand out when viewed in between two crossed polarizers, as seen in the photograph, above.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Likewise, in chemistry, rotation of polarization axes in a liquid solution can be a useful measurement.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] In a liquid, linear birefringence is impossible, but there may be circular birefringence when a chiral molecule is in solution.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] When the right and left handed enantiomers of such a molecule are present in equal numbers (a so-called racemic mixture) then their effects cancel out.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] This is measured using a polarimeter in which polarized light is passed through a tube of the liquid, at the end of which is another polarizer which is rotated in order to null the transmission of light through it.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] In many areas of astronomy, the study of polarized electromagnetic radiation from outer space is of great importance.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Apart from providing information on sources of radiation and scattering, polarization also probes the interstellar magnetic field via Faraday rotation.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] The polarization of the cosmic microwave background is being used to study the physics of the very early universe.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] Synchrotron radiation is inherently polarized.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p01] It has been suggested that astronomical sources caused the chirality of biological molecules on Earth, but chirality selection on inorganic crystals has been proposed as an alternative theory.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] Unpolarized light, after being reflected by a specular (shiny) surface, generally obtains a degree of polarization.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] This phenomenon was observed in the early 1800s by the mathematician Étienne-Louis Malus, after whom Malus's law is named.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] Polarizing sunglasses exploit this effect to reduce glare from reflections by horizontal surfaces, notably the road ahead viewed at a grazing angle.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] Wearers of polarized sunglasses will occasionally observe inadvertent polarization effects such as color-dependent birefringent effects, for example in toughened glass (e.g., car windows) or items made from transparent plastics, in conjunction with natural polarization by reflection or scattering.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] The polarized light from liquid-crystal display (LCD) monitors (see below) is extremely conspicuous when these are worn.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] Polarization is observed in the light of the sky, as this is due to sunlight scattered by aerosols as it passes through Earth's atmosphere.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] The scattered light produces the brightness and color in clear skies.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] This partial polarization of scattered light can be used to darken the sky in photographs, increasing the contrast.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] This effect is most strongly observed at points on the sky making a 90° angle to the Sun.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] Polarizing filters use these effects to optimize the results of photographing scenes in which reflection or scattering by the sky is involved.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] Sky polarization has been used for orientation in navigation.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] The Pfund sky compass was used in the 1950s when navigating near the poles of the Earth's magnetic field when neither the sun nor stars were visible (e.g., under daytime cloud or twilight).
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] It has been suggested, controversially, that the Vikings exploited a similar device (the "sunstone") in their extensive expeditions across the North Atlantic in the 9th–11th centuries, before the arrival of the magnetic compass from Asia to Europe in the 12th century.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] Related to the sky compass is the "polar clock", invented by Charles Wheatstone in the late 19th century.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] The principle of liquid-crystal display (LCD) technology relies on the rotation of the axis of linear polarization by the liquid crystal array.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] Light from the backlight (or the back reflective layer, in devices not including or requiring a backlight) first passes through a linear polarizing sheet.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] That polarized light passes through the actual liquid crystal layer which may be organized in pixels (for a TV or computer monitor) or in another format such as a seven-segment display or one with custom symbols for a particular product.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] The liquid crystal layer is produced with a consistent right (or left) handed chirality, essentially consisting of tiny helices.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] This causes circular birefringence, and is engineered so that there is a 90 degree rotation of the linear polarization state.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] However, when a voltage is applied across a cell, the molecules straighten out, lessening or totally losing the circular birefringence.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] On the viewing side of the display is another linear polarizing sheet, usually oriented at 90 degrees from the one behind the active layer.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] Therefore, when the circular birefringence is removed by the application of a sufficient voltage, the polarization of the transmitted light remains at right angles to the front polarizer, and the pixel appears dark.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] With no voltage, however, the 90 degree rotation of the polarization causes it to exactly match the axis of the front polarizer, allowing the light through.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] Intermediate voltages create intermediate rotation of the polarization axis and the pixel has an intermediate intensity.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] Displays based on this principle are widespread, and now are used in the vast majority of televisions, computer monitors and video projectors, rendering the previous CRT technology essentially obsolete.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] The use of polarization in the operation of LCDs is immediately apparent to someone wearing polarized sunglasses, often making the display unreadable.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] In a totally different sense, polarization encoding has become the leading (but not sole) method for delivering separate images to the left and right eye in stereoscopic displays used for 3D movies.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] This involves separate images intended for each eye either projected from two different projectors with orthogonally oriented polarizing filters or, more typically, from a single projector with time multiplexed polarization (a fast alternating polarization device for successive frames).
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] Polarized 3D glasses with suitable polarizing filters ensure that each eye receives only the intended image.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] Historically such systems used linear polarization encoding because it was inexpensive and offered good separation.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] However, circular polarization makes separation of the two images insensitive to tilting of the head, and is widely used in 3-D movie exhibition today, such as the system from RealD.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] Projecting such images requires screens that maintain the polarization of the projected light when viewed in reflection (such as silver screens); a normal diffuse white projection screen causes depolarization of the projected images, making it unsuitable for this application.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] Although now obsolete, CRT computer displays suffered from reflection by the glass envelope, causing glare from room lights and consequently poor contrast.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] Several anti-reflection solutions were employed to ameliorate this problem.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] One solution utilized the principle of reflection of circularly polarized light.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] A circular polarizing filter in front of the screen allows for the transmission of (say) only right circularly polarized room light.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] Now, right circularly polarized light (depending on the convention used) has its electric (and magnetic) field direction rotating clockwise while propagating in the +z direction.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] Upon reflection, the field still has the same direction of rotation, but now propagation is in the −z direction making the reflected wave *left* circularly polarized.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] With the right circular polarization filter placed in front of the reflecting glass, the unwanted light reflected from the glass will thus be in very polarization state that is *blocked* by that filter, eliminating the reflection problem.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] The reversal of circular polarization on reflection and elimination of reflections in this manner can be easily observed by looking in a mirror while wearing 3-D movie glasses which employ left- and right-handed circular polarization in the two lenses.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] Closing one eye, the other eye will see a reflection in which it cannot see itself; that lens appears black.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] However, the other lens (of the closed eye) will have the correct circular polarization allowing the closed eye to be easily seen by the open one.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] All radio (and microwave) antennas used for transmitting or receiving are intrinsically polarized.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] They transmit in (or receive signals from) a particular polarization, being totally insensitive to the opposite polarization; in certain cases that polarization is a function of direction.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] Most antennas are nominally linearly polarized, but elliptical and circular polarization is a possibility.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] In the case of linear polarization, the same kind of filtering as described above, is possible.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] In the case of elliptical polarization (circular polarization is in reality just a kind of elliptical polarization where the length of both elasticity factors is the same), filtering out a single angle (e.g.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] 90°) will have virtually no impact as the wave at any time can be in any of the 360 degrees.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] The vast majority of antennas are linearly polarized.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] In fact it can be shown from considerations of symmetry that an antenna that lies entirely in a plane which also includes the observer, can *only* have its polarization in the direction of that plane.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] This applies to many cases, allowing one to easily infer such an antenna's polarization at an intended direction of propagation.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] So a typical rooftop Yagi or log-periodic antenna with horizontal conductors, as viewed from a second station toward the horizon, is necessarily horizontally polarized.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] But a vertical "whip antenna" or AM broadcast tower used as an antenna element (again, for observers horizontally displaced from it) will transmit in the vertical polarization.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] A turnstile antenna with its four arms in the horizontal plane, likewise transmits horizontally polarized radiation toward the horizon.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] However, when that same turnstile antenna is used in the "axial mode" (upwards, for the same horizontally-oriented structure) its radiation is circularly polarized.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] At intermediate elevations it is elliptically polarized.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] Polarization is important in radio communications because, for instance, if one attempts to use a horizontally polarized antenna to receive a vertically polarized transmission, the signal strength will be substantially reduced (or under very controlled conditions, reduced to nothing).
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] This principle is used in satellite television in order to double the channel capacity over a fixed frequency band.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] The same frequency channel can be used for two signals broadcast in opposite polarizations.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] By adjusting the receiving antenna for one or the other polarization, either signal can be selected without interference from the other.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] Especially due to the presence of the ground, there are some differences in propagation (and also in reflections responsible for TV ghosting) between horizontal and vertical polarizations.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] AM and FM broadcast radio usually use vertical polarization, while television uses horizontal polarization.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] At low frequencies especially, horizontal polarization is avoided.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] That is because the phase of a horizontally polarized wave is reversed upon reflection by the ground.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] A distant station in the horizontal direction will receive both the direct and reflected wave, which thus tend to cancel each other.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] This problem is avoided with vertical polarization.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] Polarization is also important in the transmission of radar pulses and reception of radar reflections by the same or a different antenna.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] For instance, back scattering of radar pulses by rain drops can be avoided by using circular polarization.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] Just as specular reflection of circularly polarized light reverses the handedness of the polarization, as discussed above, the same principle applies to scattering by objects much smaller than a wavelength such as rain drops.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] On the other hand, reflection of that wave by an irregular metal object (such as an airplane) will typically introduce a change in polarization and (partial) reception of the return wave by the same antenna.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] The effect of free electrons in the ionosphere, in conjunction with the earth's magnetic field, causes Faraday rotation, a sort of circular birefringence.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] This is the same mechanism which can rotate the axis of linear polarization by electrons in interstellar space as mentioned below.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] The magnitude of Faraday rotation caused by such a plasma is greatly exaggerated at lower frequencies, so at the higher microwave frequencies used by satellites the effect is minimal.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] However, medium or short wave transmissions received following refraction by the ionosphere are strongly affected.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] Since a wave's path through the ionosphere and the earth's magnetic field vector along such a path are rather unpredictable, a wave transmitted with vertical (or horizontal) polarization will generally have a resulting polarization in an arbitrary orientation at the receiver.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] Many animals are capable of perceiving some of the components of the polarization of light, e.g., linear horizontally polarized light.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] This is generally used for navigational purposes, since the linear polarization of sky light is always perpendicular to the direction of the sun.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] This ability is very common among the insects, including bees, which use this information to orient their communicative dances.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] Polarization sensitivity has also been observed in species of octopus, squid, cuttlefish, and mantis shrimp.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] In the latter case, one species, *Gonodactylus smithii*, measures all six orthogonal components of polarization, and is believed to have optimal polarization vision.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] The rapidly changing, vividly colored skin patterns of cuttlefish, used for communication, also incorporate polarization patterns, and mantis shrimp are known to have polarization selective reflective tissue.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] Sky polarization was thought to be perceived by pigeons, which was assumed to be one of their aids in homing, but research indicates this is a popular myth.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] The naked human eye is weakly sensitive to polarization, without the need for intervening filters.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] Polarized light creates a very faint pattern near the center of the visual field, called Haidinger's brush.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] This pattern is very difficult to see, but with practice one can learn to detect polarized light with the naked eye.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] It is well known that electromagnetic radiation carries a certain linear momentum in the direction of propagation.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] In addition, however, light carries a certain angular momentum if it is circularly polarized (or partially so).
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] In comparison with lower frequencies such as microwaves, the amount of angular momentum in light, even of pure circular polarization, compared to the same wave's linear momentum (or radiation pressure) is very small and difficult to even measure.
[src:optics-physics/polarization-waves-p02] However, it was utilized in an experiment to achieve speeds of up to 600 million revolutions per minute.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] In acoustics, reflection causes echoes and is used in sonar.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] In geology, it is important in the study of seismic waves.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] Reflection is observed with surface waves in bodies of water.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] Reflection is observed with many types of electromagnetic wave, besides visible light.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] Reflection of VHF and higher frequencies is important for radio transmission and for radar.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] Even hard X-rays and gamma rays can be reflected at shallow angles with special "grazing" mirrors.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] Reflection of light is either *specular* (mirror-like) or *diffuse* (retaining the energy, but losing the image) depending on the nature of the interface.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] In specular reflection the phase of the reflected waves depends on the choice of the origin of coordinates, but the relative phase between s and p (TE and TM) polarizations is fixed by the properties of the media and of the interface between them.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] A mirror provides the most common model for specular light reflection, and typically consists of a glass sheet with a metallic coating where the significant reflection occurs.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] Reflection is enhanced in metals by suppression of wave propagation beyond their skin depths.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] Reflection also occurs at the surface of transparent media, such as water or glass, although the reflection is generally less effective compared with mirrors.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] In the diagram, a light ray **PO** strikes a vertical mirror at point **O**, and the reflected ray is **OQ**.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] By projecting an imaginary line through point **O** perpendicular to the mirror, known as the *normal*, we can measure the *angle of incidence*, *θ*i and the *angle of reflection*, *θ*r.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] The *law of reflection* states that *θ*i = *θ*r, or in other words, the angle of incidence equals the angle of reflection.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] The wave vector of the reflected wave is such that its vector projection on the mirror normal is the negation of that of the incident wave vector while the magnitude (wavenumber) is the same.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] In fact, reflection of light may occur whenever light travels from a medium of a given refractive index into a medium with a different refractive index.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] In the most general case, a certain fraction of the light is reflected from the interface, and the remainder is refracted.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] Solving Maxwell's equations for a light ray striking a boundary allows the derivation of the Fresnel equations, which can be used to predict how much of the light is reflected, and how much is refracted in a given situation.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] This is analogous to the way impedance mismatch in an electric circuit causes reflection of signals.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] Total internal reflection of light from a denser medium occurs if the angle of incidence is greater than the critical angle.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] Total internal reflection is used as a means of focusing waves that cannot effectively be reflected by common means.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] X-ray telescopes are constructed by creating a converging "tunnel" for the waves.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] As the waves interact at low angle with the surface of this tunnel they are reflected toward the focus point (or toward another interaction with the tunnel surface, eventually being directed to the detector at the focus).
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] A conventional reflector would be useless as the X-rays would simply pass through the intended reflector.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] When light reflects off a material with higher refractive index than the medium in which is traveling, it undergoes a 180° phase shift.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] In contrast, when light reflects off a material with lower refractive index the reflected light is in phase with the incident light.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] This is an important principle in the field of thin-film optics.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] Reflection from a flat surface forms a mirror image, which appears to be reversed from left to right because we compare the image we see to what we would see if we were rotated into the position of the image.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] Specular reflection at a curved surface forms an image which may be magnified or demagnified; curved mirrors have optical power.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] Such mirrors may have surfaces that are spherical or parabolic.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] If the reflecting surface is very smooth, the reflection of light that occurs is called specular or regular reflection.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] The angle which the incident ray makes with the normal is equal to the angle which the reflected ray makes to the same normal.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] The reflected ray and the incident ray are on the opposite sides of the normal.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] These three laws can all be derived from the Fresnel equations.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] In classical electrodynamics, light is considered as an electromagnetic wave, which is described by Maxwell's equations.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] Light waves incident on a material induce small oscillations of polarisation in the individual atoms (or oscillation of electrons, in metals), causing each particle to radiate a small secondary wave in all directions, like a dipole antenna.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] All these waves add up to give specular reflection and refraction, according to the Huygens–Fresnel principle.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] In the case of dielectrics such as glass, the electric field of the light acts on the electrons in the material, and the moving electrons generate fields and become new radiators.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] The refracted light in the glass is the combination of the forward radiation of the electrons and the incident light.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] The reflected light is the combination of the backward radiation of all of the electrons.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] In metals, electrons with no binding energy are called free electrons.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] When these electrons oscillate with the incident light, the phase difference between their radiation field and the incident field is π radians (180°), so the forward radiation cancels the incident light, and backward radiation is just the reflected light.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] Light–matter interaction in terms of photons is a topic of quantum electrodynamics, and is described in detail by Richard Feynman in his popular book *QED: The Strange Theory of Light and Matter*.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] The exact form of the reflection depends on the structure of the material.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] One common model for diffuse reflection is Lambertian reflectance, in which the light is reflected with equal luminance (in photometry) or radiance (in radiometry) in all directions, as defined by Lambert's cosine law.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] The light sent to our eyes by most of the objects we see is due to diffuse reflection from their surface, so that this is our primary mechanism of physical observation.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] Some surfaces exhibit *retroreflection*.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] The structure of these surfaces is such that light is returned in the direction from which it came.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] When flying over clouds illuminated by sunlight the region seen around the aircraft's shadow will appear brighter, and a similar effect may be seen from dew on grass.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] This partial retro-reflection is created by the refractive properties of the curved droplet's surface and reflective properties at the backside of the droplet.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] Some animals' retinas act as retroreflectors (see *tapetum lucidum* for more detail), as this effectively improves the animals' night vision.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] Since the lenses of their eyes modify reciprocally the paths of the incoming and outgoing light the effect is that the eyes act as a strong retroreflector, sometimes seen at night when walking in wildlands with a flashlight.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] A simple retroreflector can be made by placing three ordinary mirrors mutually perpendicular to one another (a corner reflector).
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] The image produced is the inverse of one produced by a single mirror.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] A surface can be made partially retroreflective by depositing a layer of tiny refractive spheres on it or by creating small pyramid like structures.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] In both cases internal reflection causes the light to be reflected back to where it originated.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] This is used to make traffic signs and automobile license plates reflect light mostly back in the direction from which it came.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] In this application perfect retroreflection is not desired, since the light would then be directed back into the headlights of an oncoming car rather than to the driver's eyes.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] When light reflects off a mirror, one image appears.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] Two mirrors placed exactly face to face give the appearance of an infinite number of images along a straight line.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] The multiple images seen between two mirrors that sit at an angle to each other lie over a circle.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] The center of that circle is located at the imaginary intersection of the mirrors.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] A square of four mirrors placed face to face give the appearance of an infinite number of images arranged in a plane.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] The multiple images seen between four mirrors assembling a pyramid, in which each pair of mirrors sits an angle to each other, lie over a sphere.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] If the base of the pyramid is rectangle shaped, the images spread over a section of a torus.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] Note that these are theoretical ideals, requiring perfect alignment of perfectly smooth, perfectly flat perfect reflectors that absorb none of the light.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] In practice, these situations can only be approached but not achieved because the effects of any surface imperfections in the reflectors propagate and magnify, absorption gradually extinguishes the image, and any observing equipment (biological or technological) will interfere.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] In this process (which is also known as phase conjugation), light bounces exactly back in the direction from which it came due to a nonlinear optical process.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] Not only the direction of the light is reversed, but the actual wavefronts are reversed as well.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] A conjugate reflector can be used to remove aberrations from a beam by reflecting it and then passing the reflection through the aberrating optics a second time.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] If one were to look into a complex conjugating mirror, it would be black because only the photons which left the pupil would reach the pupil.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] Materials that reflect neutrons, for example beryllium, are used in nuclear reactors and nuclear weapons.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] In the physical and biological sciences, the reflection of neutrons off atoms within a material is commonly used to determine the material's internal structure.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] When a longitudinal sound wave strikes a flat surface, sound is reflected in a coherent manner provided that the dimension of the reflective surface is large compared to the wavelength of the sound.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] Note that audible sound has a very wide frequency range (from 20 to about 17000 Hz), and thus a very wide range of wavelengths (from about 20 mm to 17 m).
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] As a result, the overall nature of the reflection varies according to the texture and structure of the surface.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] For example, porous materials will absorb some energy, and rough materials (where rough is relative to the wavelength) tend to reflect in many directions—to scatter the energy, rather than to reflect it coherently.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] This leads into the field of architectural acoustics, because the nature of these reflections is critical to the auditory feel of a space.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] In the theory of exterior noise mitigation, reflective surface size mildly detracts from the concept of a noise barrier by reflecting some of the sound into the opposite direction.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] Sound reflection can affect the acoustic space.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] Seismic waves produced by earthquakes or other sources (such as explosions) may be reflected by layers within the Earth.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] Study of the deep reflections of waves generated by earthquakes has allowed seismologists to determine the layered structure of the Earth.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] Shallower reflections are used in reflection seismology to study the Earth's crust generally, and in particular to prospect for petroleum and natural gas deposits.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] Scientists have speculated that there could be time reflections.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] Scientists from the Advanced Science Research Center at the CUNY Graduate Center report that they observed time reflections by sending broadband signals into a strip of metamaterial filled with electronic switches.
[src:optics-physics/reflection-physics] The "time reflections" in electromagnetic waves are discussed in a 2023 paper published in the journal *Nature Physics*.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] In physics, **refraction** is the redirection of a wave as it passes from one medium to another.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] The redirection can be caused by the wave's change in speed or by a change in the medium.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] Refraction of light is the most commonly observed phenomenon, but other waves such as sound waves and water waves also experience refraction.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] How much a wave is refracted is determined by the change in wave speed and the initial direction of wave propagation relative to the direction of change in speed.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] Optical prisms and lenses use refraction to redirect light, as does the human eye.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] The refractive index of materials varies with the wavelength of light, and thus the angle of the refraction also varies correspondingly.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] This is called dispersion and allows certain prisms and raindrops in rainbows to divide white light into its constituent spectral colors.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] Refraction involves two related parts, both a result of the wave nature of light: a reduced speed in an optical medium and a change in angle when a wave front crosses between different media at an angle.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] When light enters a slower medium at an angle, one side of the wavefront is slowed before the other.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] This asymmetrical slowing of the light causes it to change the angle of its travel.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] Once light is within the new medium with constant properties, it travels in a straight line again.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] As described above, the speed of light is slower in a medium other than vacuum.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] This slowing applies to any medium such as air, water, or glass, and is responsible for phenomena such as refraction.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] On the other side of the medium its speed will again be the speed of light in vacuum, c.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] A correct explanation rests on light's nature as an electromagnetic wave.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] Because light is an oscillating electrical/magnetic wave, light traveling in a medium causes the electrically charged electrons of the material to also oscillate.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] (The material's protons also oscillate but as they are around 2000 times more massive, their movement and therefore their effect, is far smaller).
[src:optics-physics/refraction] A moving electrical charge emits electromagnetic waves of its own.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] The electromagnetic waves emitted by the oscillating electrons interact with the electromagnetic waves that make up the original light, similar to water waves on a pond, a process known as constructive interference.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] When two waves interfere in this way, the resulting "combined" wave may have wave packets that pass an observer at a slower rate.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] When the light leaves the material, this interaction with electrons no longer happens, and therefore the wave packet rate (and therefore its speed) return to normal.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] Consider a wave going from one material to another where its speed is slower as in the figure.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] If it reaches the interface between the materials at an angle one side of the wave will reach the second material first, and therefore slow down earlier.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] With one side of the wave going slower the whole wave will pivot towards that side.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] This is why a wave will bend away from the surface or toward the normal when going into a slower material.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] In the opposite case of a wave reaching a material where the speed is higher, one side of the wave will speed up and the wave will pivot away from that side.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] Another way of understanding the same thing is to consider the change in wavelength at the interface.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] When the wave goes from one material to another where the wave has a different speed v, the frequency f of the wave will stay the same, but the distance between wavefronts or wavelength *λ* = *v*/*f* will change.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] If the speed is decreased, such as in the figure to the right, the wavelength will also decrease.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] With an angle between the wave fronts and the interface and change in distance between the wave fronts the angle must change over the interface to keep the wave fronts intact.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] From these considerations the relationship between the angle of incidence *θ*1, angle of transmission *θ*2 and the wave speeds *v*1 and *v*2 in the two materials can be derived.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] The phenomenon of refraction can in a more fundamental way be derived from the 2 or 3-dimensional wave equation.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] The boundary condition at the interface will then require the tangential component of the wave vector to be identical on the two sides of the interface.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] Since the magnitude of the wave vector depend on the wave speed this requires a change in direction of the wave vector.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] The relevant wave speed in the discussion above is the phase velocity of the wave.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] This is typically close to the group velocity which can be seen as the truer speed of a wave, but when they differ it is important to use the phase velocity in all calculations relating to refraction.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] A wave traveling perpendicular to a boundary, i.e. having its wavefronts parallel to the boundary, will not change direction even if the speed of the wave changes.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] Refraction is also responsible for rainbows and for the splitting of white light into a rainbow-spectrum as it passes through a glass prism.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] Glass and water have higher refractive indexes than air.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] The different colors correspond to different frequencies and different wavelengths.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] Refraction occurs when light goes through a water surface since water has a refractive index of 1.33 and air has a refractive index of about 1.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] Looking at a straight object, such as a pencil in the figure here, which is placed at a slant, partially in the water, the object appears to bend at the water's surface.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] This is due to the bending of light rays as they move from the water to the air.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] Once the rays reach the eye, the eye traces them back as straight lines (lines of sight).
[src:optics-physics/refraction] The lines of sight (shown as dashed lines) intersect at a higher position than where the actual rays originated.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] This causes the pencil to appear higher and the water to appear shallower than it really is.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] The depth that the water appears to be when viewed from above is known as the *apparent depth*.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] This is an important consideration for spearfishing from the surface because it will make the target fish appear to be in a different place, and the fisher must aim lower to catch the fish.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] Conversely, an object above the water has a higher *apparent height* when viewed from below the water.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] The opposite correction must be made by an archer fish.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] For small angles of incidence (measured from the normal, when sin *θ* is approximately the same as tan *θ*), the ratio of apparent to real depth is the ratio of the refractive indexes of air to that of water.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] But, as the angle of incidence approaches 90°, the apparent depth approaches zero, albeit reflection increases, which limits observation at high angles of incidence.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] Conversely, the apparent height approaches infinity as the angle of incidence (from below) increases, but even earlier, as the angle of total internal reflection is approached, albeit the image also fades from view as this limit is approached.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] The refractive index of air depends on the air density and thus vary with air temperature and pressure.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] Since the pressure is lower at higher altitudes, the refractive index is also lower, causing light rays to refract towards the earth surface when traveling long distances through the atmosphere.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] This shifts the apparent positions of stars slightly when they are close to the horizon and makes the sun visible before it geometrically rises above the horizon during a sunrise.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] Temperature variations in the air can also cause refraction of light.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] This can be seen as a heat haze when hot and cold air is mixed e.g. over a fire, in engine exhaust, or when opening a window on a cold day.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] This makes objects viewed through the mixed air appear to shimmer or move around randomly as the hot and cold air moves.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] This effect is also visible from normal variations in air temperature during a sunny day when using high magnification telephoto lenses and is often limiting the image quality in these cases.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] In a similar way, atmospheric turbulence gives rapidly varying distortions in the images of astronomical telescopes limiting the resolution of terrestrial telescopes not using adaptive optics or other techniques for overcoming these atmospheric distortions.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] Air temperature variations close to the surface can give rise to other optical phenomena, such as mirages and Fata Morgana.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] Most commonly, air heated by a hot road on a sunny day deflects light approaching at a shallow angle towards a viewer.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] This makes the road appear reflecting, giving an illusion of water covering the road.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] In medicine, particularly optometry, ophthalmology and orthoptics, *refraction* (also known as *refractometry*) is a clinical test in which a phoropter may be used by the appropriate eye care professional to determine the eye's refractive error and the best corrective lenses to be prescribed.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] A series of test lenses in graded optical powers or focal lengths are presented to determine which provides the sharpest, clearest vision.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] Refractive surgery is a medical procedure to treat common vision disorders.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] Water waves travel slower in shallower water.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] This can be used to demonstrate refraction in ripple tanks and also explains why waves on a shoreline tend to strike the shore close to a perpendicular angle.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] As the waves travel from deep water into shallower water near the shore, they are refracted from their original direction of travel to an angle more normal to the shoreline.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] In underwater acoustics, refraction is the bending or curving of a sound ray that results when the ray passes through a sound speed gradient from a region of one sound speed to a region of a different speed.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] The amount of ray bending is dependent on the amount of difference between sound speeds, that is, the variation in temperature, salinity, and pressure of the water.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] Similar acoustics effects are also found in the Earth's atmosphere.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] The phenomenon of refraction of sound in the atmosphere has been known for centuries.
[src:optics-physics/refraction] Beginning in the early 1970s, widespread analysis of this effect came into vogue through the designing of urban highways and noise barriers to address the meteorological effects of bending of sound rays in the lower atmosphere.
[src:optics-physics/snell-s-law] The law follows from Fermat's principle of least time, which in turn follows from the propagation of light as waves.
[src:optics-physics/snell-s-law] Ptolemy, in Alexandria, Egypt, had found a relationship regarding refraction angles, but it was inaccurate for angles that were not small.
[src:optics-physics/snell-s-law] Ptolemy was confident he had found an accurate empirical law, partially as a result of slightly altering his data to fit theory (see: confirmation bias).
[src:optics-physics/snell-s-law] The law was eventually named after Snell, although it was first discovered by the Persian scientist Ibn Sahl, at Baghdad court in 984.
[src:optics-physics/snell-s-law] In the manuscript *On Burning Mirrors and Lenses*, Sahl used the law to derive lens shapes that focus light with no geometric aberration.
[src:optics-physics/snell-s-law] Ibn al-Haytham, in his *Book of Optics* (1021), came close to rediscovering the law of refraction, but he did not take this step.
[src:optics-physics/snell-s-law] The law was rediscovered by Thomas Harriot in 1602, who however did not publish his results although he had corresponded with Kepler on this very subject.
[src:optics-physics/snell-s-law] In 1621, the Dutch astronomer Willebrord Snellius (1580–1626)—Snell—derived a mathematically equivalent form, that remained unpublished during his lifetime.
[src:optics-physics/snell-s-law] René Descartes independently derived the law using heuristic momentum conservation arguments in terms of sines in his 1637 essay *La Dioptrique*, and used it to solve a range of optical problems.
[src:optics-physics/snell-s-law] Rejecting Descartes' solution, Pierre de Fermat arrived at the same solution based solely on his principle of least time.
[src:optics-physics/snell-s-law] Descartes assumed the speed of light was infinite, yet in his derivation of Snell's law he also assumed the denser the medium, the greater the speed of light.
[src:optics-physics/snell-s-law] Fermat supported the opposing assumptions, i.e., the speed of light is finite, and his derivation depended upon the speed of light being slower in a denser medium.
[src:optics-physics/snell-s-law] Fermat's derivation also utilized his invention of adequality, a mathematical procedure equivalent to differential calculus, for finding maxima, minima, and tangents.
[src:optics-physics/snell-s-law] In his influential mathematics book *Geometry*, Descartes solves a problem that was worked on by Apollonius of Perga and Pappus of Alexandria.
[src:optics-physics/snell-s-law] Given n lines L and a point P(L) on each line, find the locus of points Q such that the lengths of the line segments QP(L) satisfy certain conditions.
[src:optics-physics/snell-s-law] For example, when n = 4, given the lines a, b, c, and d and a point A on a, B on b, and so on, find the locus of points Q such that the product QA*QB equals the product QC*QD.
[src:optics-physics/snell-s-law] When the lines are not all parallel, Pappus showed that the loci are conics, but when Descartes considered larger n, he obtained cubic and higher degree curves.
[src:optics-physics/snell-s-law] To show that the cubic curves were interesting, he showed that they arose naturally in optics from Snell's law.
[src:optics-physics/snell-s-law] According to Dijksterhuis, "In *De natura lucis et proprietate* (1662) Isaac Vossius said that Descartes had seen Snell's paper and concocted his own proof.
[src:optics-physics/snell-s-law] We now know this charge to be undeserved but it has been adopted many times since." Both Fermat and Huygens repeated this accusation that Descartes had copied Snell.
[src:optics-physics/snell-s-law] In French, Snell's Law is sometimes called "la loi de Descartes" or more frequently "*loi de Snell-Descartes*".
[src:optics-physics/snell-s-law] In his 1678 *Traité de la Lumière*, Christiaan Huygens showed how Snell's law of sines could be explained by, or derived from, the wave nature of light, using what we have come to call the Huygens–Fresnel principle.
[src:optics-physics/snell-s-law] With the development of modern optical and electromagnetic theory, Snell's law was redefined.
[src:optics-physics/snell-s-law] In 1962, Nicolaas Bloembergen showed that at the boundary of nonlinear medium, Snell's law could be written in a general form.
[src:optics-physics/snell-s-law] In 2008 and 2011, plasmonic metasurfaces were also demonstrated to change the reflection and refraction directions of light beam.
[src:optics-physics/snell-s-law] Snell's law is used to determine the direction of light rays through refractive media with varying indices of refraction.
[src:optics-physics/snell-s-law] The indices of refraction of the media, labeled $n_{1}$ , $n_{2}$ and so on, are used to represent the factor by which a light ray's speed decreases when traveling through a refractive medium, such as glass or water, as opposed to its velocity in a vacuum.
[src:optics-physics/snell-s-law] As light passes the border between media, depending upon the relative refractive indices of the two media, the light will either be refracted to a lesser angle, or a greater one.
[src:optics-physics/snell-s-law] These angles are measured with respect to the *normal line*, represented perpendicular to the boundary.
[src:optics-physics/snell-s-law] In the case of light traveling from air into water, light would be refracted towards the normal line, because the light is slowed down in water; light traveling from water to air would refract away from the normal line.
